{[%evp 0,142,19,31,72,53,51,40,29,35,47,35,44,30,77,46,24,16,20,9,22,-8,6,-3,
-13,-11,-7,-16,64,22,26,-22,-50,-49,-49,-27,25,7,16,-52,-20,-53,-48,-35,-35,
-24,-16,-5,61,1,20,13,26,-25,-25,-37,-34,-32,-32,-47,-59,-45,-24,-60,-65,-48,
-38,-29,-24,-26,-33,-53,-11,-21,3,0,60,-46,-13,-65,-79,-71,-1,-31,-13,-50,-45,
-50,-39,-19,29,26,48,-14,-21,-30,-21,-21,0,0,-12,-27,-43,-30,0,0,0,0,0,0,-18,
-41,-24,-34,-34,-28,-27,-30,-31,-92,-108,-97,-97,-118,-135,-156,-159,-162,-131,
-150,-115,-141,-125,-116,-106,-129,-106,-162,-201,-201,-201,-493,-528,-521,
-608] I would like to start the lecture with 3 classical games. We can say
that these games had a big impact on the development of the conceptual
framework of the Rauzer Variation. All the games feature a similar pattern -
Black sacrifices a pawn in order to get a bishop pair in the endgame. Our
first example will be the game Khasin - Simagin. The critical position arises
after move 13.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4 Bd7
7. Bb3 e6 8. Bg5 a6 9. O-O Be7 10. Nde2 Qc7 11. Qd2 h6 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Rad1 {
[%csl Bd7,Bf6,Bd6] Now, Black should decide how to handle the pressure on the
d6-pawn. If he opts for the passive 13...Be7, White would follow with the
advance f2-f4-f5, thus increasing the pressure along the a2-g8 diagonal.
Instead, Black opts for} g5 $5 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge5c4] Simagin sacrifices a pawn
in order to obtain an endgame with a bishop pair. In general, the advance ...
g7-g5 is very typical for Sicilian positions. The idea is to secure the
e5-square for the knight.} 14. f4 {Khasin does not accept the challenge
immediately.} ({Let's take a look at the position arising after} 14. Qxd6 Be5 {
[%cal Be5h2]} 15. Qxc7 Bxc7 {[%csl Be5][%cal Bc6e5,Be8e7,Bb7b5,Ba6a5,Bc7b6,
Bh6h5,Bh5h4,Bh4h3] Black has a big advantage in this typical Sicilian endgame.
For sure, his next moves would be ...Ne5 followed by ...Ke7. As a rule, the
side having a bishop pair should gain space on the wings. Therefore, Black can
consider playing ...b7-b5 followed by ...a6-a5. On the kingside, the advance
of the h-pawn all the way to h3 looks very promising. On the other hand,
having restricted minor pieces, White can hardly find a constructive plan in
this position.}) 14... O-O-O 15. fxg5 Bxg5 16. Qxd6 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 {This is the
position Black was looking for. The control of the dark-squares (especially
e5-square), as well as the bishop pair, provide more than enough compensation
for the pawn.} Kc7 18. Rdd1 Ne5 {[%csl Be5,Bd7,Bg5,Be4,Bg2][%cal Bd7c6,Bb7b5,
Ba6a5] Black's advantage becomes more and more visible. After putting his
bishop on c6, Black can already consider gaining space on the queenside.
Meanwhile, in such structures, White should always reckon with the vulnerable
e4 and g2-pawns.} 19. h3 Bc6 20. Kf2 {This move is a bit dubious. For sure,
the king would have been better placed on h1.} Be7 {[%cal Ge7c5] The bishop is
heading to the important diagonal a7-g1.} 21. Nf4 Rxd1 $1 {In such endgames, I
strongly advise you to exchange one pair of rooks. This is often the best way
to reduce the opponent's counterplay. On the other hand, exchanging all the
rooks does not make so much sense because it will be much more difficult for
us to attack the targets in White's camp.} 22. Rxd1 Bc5+ 23. Ke2 b5 $2 {
Even though this move is positionally correct, it does not work tactically.} ({
Black should have started with} 23... Bd6 {[%csl Re4,Rg2][%cal Gb7b5,Ga6a5,
Gh6h5,Gh5h4] Besides gaining space on the queenside, he can also fix the
g2-pawn by means of ...h6-h5-h4.}) 24. Nd3 $2 {White misses his chance to
punish the move ...b5.} ({He should have played} 24. Bxe6 $1 {when the
following sequence is possible -} fxe6 25. Nxe6+ Kb6 26. Nd5+ $1 Bxd5 27. Rxd5
Ng6 28. Rxc5 Re8 29. Nc7 Rxe4+ {[#]} 30. Kf3 $1 Re7 31. Nxa6 $16 {White has a
clear advantage.}) 24... Bd6 25. Rf1 Rh7 26. a3 h5 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gh5h4]} 27.
Rf6 Kd7 {[%cal Gd7e7] As we are going to see on many occasions, in such
endgames, e7 is the perfect spot for the king.} 28. Rf2 h4 29. Kf1 Ke7 30. Re2
{[%cal Bc6b7,Ge2e7,Gc3d5]} Rg7 $6 {Once again, Simagin plays on general
grounds without paying attention to the tactical possibilities of his opponent.
} ({Better would have been} 30... Bb7 {anticipating the threat of Nd5+}) 31.
Nd1 $6 {White returns the favour.} ({After} 31. Nd5+ $1 Kf8 (31... exd5 $2 32.
exd5 {retrieves the piece with a clear advantage already.}) 32. N5b4 Bb7 33.
Nxe5 Bxe5 34. Nd3 {White manages to achieve a favourable regrouping.}) 31... a5
{Black already starts gaining space on the queenside.} 32. N1f2 {[%cal Gd3e5,
Gd6e5,Gf2d3]} Bb7 $5 {This time, Simagin is alert to the tactical threat.} 33.
Nxe5 Bxe5 34. Nd3 Bc7 35. c3 {[%csl Be4,Bg2][%cal Bb5b4]} Bb6 {Black's bishop
pair is already very powerful.} ({Even more convincing would have been} 35...
Rg3 $1 36. Bc2 {[#]} b4 $1 {[%cal Gb7a6] Black combines threats on both wings.}
37. Nc5 ({After} 37. axb4 Ba6 38. Rd2 axb4 39. cxb4 Bb6 $19 {Black is winning.}
) 37... Bc6 {[%cal Gc6b5]} 38. Ba4 $1 Bxa4 39. Nxa4 bxa3 40. bxa3 Bf4 41. Rb2
Kd6 42. Rb5 Re3 $17 {[%cal Gf4g3] Besides attacking on e4, Black wants to play
...Bg3 as well.}) 36. Ne5 {Now, Black does not have the tactical ideas from
the previous line. His positional advantage, however, is quite stable. Later
on, he managed to win by playing on both wings.} Bc7 {[#]} 37. Nf3 Rg3 38. Bc2
b4 39. Rd2 bxa3 40. bxa3 Rg8 41. Bd3 $1 Rb8 {[#]} 42. Rd1 $6 Bc6 43. Nd4 Ba4
44. Rb1 {[#]} Rc8 $2 45. Rb7 Kf6 {[#]} 46. Ne2 Be5 47. Ra7 Rc5 48. Ke1 Bb3 49.
Kd2 Bh2 50. Nd4 Bf4+ 51. Ke2 Rxc3 52. Nxb3 Rxb3 53. Rxa5 Rb2+ 54. Kf3 Bg3 55.
Be2 Rb3+ 56. Kg4 Be1 57. Rb5 Rg3+ {[#]} 58. Kh5 (58. Kf4 $2 Bd2#) 58... Rxg2
59. Bc4 Rg3 {[#]} 60. Rb1 $2 Rg5+ $1 61. Kh6 Bd2 62. Kh7 Rg7+ 63. Kh8 Bc3 64.
Rb5 (64. Rb3 Rg3 65. a4 Kg6+ 66. Kg8 Rxh3 67. a5 Rg3 68. a6 h3 69. a7 h2 70.
a8=Q h1=Q $19) 64... Rg3 65. Bf1 Be5 66. a4 Rf3 $1 67. Rb1 Ra3 68. Rb4 Ra1 69.
Be2 Re1 $1 70. Bd3 Kg6+ 71. Kg8 $19 Rc1 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

