{The following game is considered to be a model example illustrating Black's
ideas in the endgame. Once again, Black sacrifices a pawn to get a favourable
endgame with a bishop pair.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3
d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 h6 {This was the pet line of Botvinnik.} ({Nowadays, Black
mostly plays} 7... a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 {Practice has shown that it's
important to win space on the queenside.}) 8. Bxf6 gxf6 {[%csl Bf7,Bf6,Be6,Bd6]
} ({Taking with the queen} 8... Qxf6 $6 {does not work because of} 9. Ndb5 Qd8
10. O-O-O {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gb5d6] when the pressure on d6 is very annoying.})
9. O-O-O a6 10. f4 Bd7 11. Bc4 {[%csl Bf7,Bf6,Be6,Bd6] With this move, White
puts pressure on the e6-pawn. His most thematic idea in this structure is the
advance f4-f5. The idea is to weaken the d5-square by provoking the advance ...
e6-e5.} ({Another typical idea is} 11. Be2 {[%csl Be2,Bh5][%cal Be2h5] when
Black should immediately play} h5 ({After a move like} 11... Rc8 $2 {White
will be more than happy to play} 12. Bh5 {[%csl Be6][%cal Bh5e8,Bf4f5,Be6e5,
Bd4e6] with the threat of f4-f5 and even Ne6 if possible. In such positions,
Black does not have counterplay.})) 11... h5 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gh8g8,Gh5h4]
Remember this typical move. Besides preventing f4-f5, Black gains space on the
kingside. In many cases (especially in the endgame), he is going to play ...
h5-h4 followed by ...Rg8, thus putting pressure on g2.} ({In the event of} 
11... Rc8 {White will play} 12. f5 {[%csl Bf5,Be6] provoking ...e6-e5.}) 12.
Kb1 (12. f5 $4 Bh6 $19) 12... Qb6 13. Rhf1 Qxd4 $1 {Botvinnik forces the
transition into a favourable endgame. As I have pointed out in the
introduction, most of the Sicilian endgames are favourable for Black.} 14. Qxd4
Nxd4 15. Rxd4 Rc8 16. Bb3 Rg8 {[%cal Gg8g2] The pressure along the g-file is a
major idea in Rauzer endgames.} 17. Rd2 ({The natural} 17. g3 {is well met by
the thematic} h4 {[%csl Rg3] when Black will create a kingside weakness in
White's camp.}) 17... h4 $1 {Another thematic move. Black takes the chance to
fix the g2-pawn.} 18. f5 {[%csl Bf6][%cal Bd2f2,Bf1f6] When the queens have
been traded off, this advance is not that threatening.} Ke7 $1 {[%csl Rb3,Re4,
Ge5,Rg2][%cal Gf8h6,Gh6f4,Gf4e5,Gb7b5,Ga6a5,Gd7c6,Ga5a4,Gg8g2] In all endgames
with doubled pawns on the f-file, e7 is the best square for the king. Now,
Black can activate his dark-squared bishop via h6. If Black manages to put the
bishop on e5, White will be lost.} 19. Rdf2 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gf2f6,Gf5e6,Gf7e6]
White puts indirect pressure on f6.} ({Let's suppose that White allows the
bishop transfer to e5 -} 19. Re1 Bh6 20. Rde2 Bf4 21. h3 Be5 {[%csl Re4,Rg2]
[%cal Gd7c6,Gb7b5,Ga6a5,Gg8g3,Gc8g8] This is Black's dream endgame position.
He can now combine his queenside play with the pressure on e4 and g2.
Meanwhile, the bishops are controlling the entire board. Even if we remove the
pawn on d6 (or the one on f6), Black will still enjoy a big advantage. This is
something that we are going to see a bit later.}) 19... Bh6 $1 {Of course!
Passive moves such as ...Bg7 shouldn't be even considered. Botvinnik
sacrifices the f6-pawn in order to achieve an activity in the endgame.} 20.
fxe6 fxe6 21. Rxf6 Rcf8 22. Rxf8 {How to recapture?} Bxf8 $1 {In order to keep
more winning chances, Black should exchange only a pair of rooks. The
remaining rook will be attacking the opponent's weaknesses. Now, Black is
going to activate his dark-squared bishop.} 23. Rf2 Bh6 {[%csl Rc3,Re4,Rg2]
[%cal Gd7c6,Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Ga6a5]} 24. Bc4 Be3 25. Re2 Bg1 {With this strong move,
Black wants to provoke the advance h2-h3. As a consequence, the g2-pawn will
become even more vulnerable. Instead, Suetin decided to give the pawn back.}
26. g3 ({After} 26. h3 {Black would have followed with} Bh2 {[%cal Gh2e5,Gg8g3,
Gd7c6,Gb7b5,Ga6a5] Planning to put the bishop on e5. Afterwards, Black can
proceed with his typical play - ...Rg3, ...Bc6 followed by advancing the
queenside pawns.}) 26... hxg3 27. hxg3 Rxg3 $17 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gg1d4,Ge7f6,
Gf6e5,Gd7c6,Gb7b5] Black has a big advantage in this endgame since he enjoys
the bishop pair for free. As there are not many pieces on the board, Black can
even consider putting the king on e5. As usual, the light-squared bishop will
occupy the c6-square. In the near future, Black will start advancing the
queenside pawns. Even though White has some chances for a draw, practically
speaking, his position is very difficult. Suetin didn't manage to hold this
endgame.} 28. a3 Be8 29. Ka2 Bh5 30. Re1 Bd4 31. Rh1 Rg5 32. Kb3 Be5 33. Bd3
Bg6 34. Rh4 Rg3 35. a4 Bf6 36. Rh1 Rg4 37. Re1 Be5 38. Nd1 Rf4 39. Nc3 Rf3 40.
Nb1 Bg3 41. Rg1 Bxe4 42. Nd2 Bd5+ 43. Ka3 Rf2 44. Ne4 Bh2 45. Rg6 Bxe4 46. Bxe4
d5 47. Bd3 Be5 48. Rg8 Kd7 49. b4 Bf6 50. Rg1 Rh2 51. Kb3 Kd6 52. Rd1 Ke7 53.
c4 Rb2+ 54. Ka3 dxc4 55. Bxc4 Rc2 56. Bb3 Bb2+ 57. Ka2 Rf2 58. Bc4 a5 59. bxa5
Bc3+ 60. Kb3 Bxa5 61. Bb5 b6 62. Kc4 Kf6 63. Kd4 Rf4+ 64. Ke3 Ke5 65. Rh1 Re4+
66. Kd3 Rg4 67. Rh5+ Kd6 68. Rh8 Ke5 69. Rh5+ Kf4 70. Rh3 Rg8 71. Rh4+ Ke5 72.
Rh5+ Kd6 73. Rh4 Rg3+ 74. Ke4 Bd2 75. Bd3 Bg5 76. Rh5 Kc5 {0-1 White resigns.}
0-1

