{[#] Let's take a look at another interesting fragment taken from the practice
of Botvinnik. The situation is quite similar to the previous game. This time,
however, Black didn't manage to activate the dark-squared bishop. That's why
the e7-square is not available for the king. Botvinnik solves these two
problems by means of a typical pawn sacrifice. At this point, he played} 18...
Bd8 $1 {Black sacrifices the d6-pawn for activity. Afterwards, the king will
go to e7 while the bishop will occupy the perfect e5-square.} 19. Rxd6 Ke7 20.
Rdd1 Bc7 21. Bf3 Be5 $15 {[%csl Ra2,Rd4,Rd5,Rd6,Rd7][%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Ga6a5,
Ga5a4,Ga4a3,Gh6h5,Gh5h4] This is the position Black was playing for. The
absence of the d6-pawn is not important at all. As you can easily see, White
does not have available squares on the d-file. In his turn, Black can start
gaining space on both wings. On the queenside, he is going to play ...b7-b5-b4
followed by ...a6-a5-a4-a3. On the kingside, he will try to create a new
weakness by employing the advance ... h6-h5-h4. Even though Botvinnik failed
to win, his position is already better.} 22. Ne2 Bb5 23. Rfe1 Rgg8 24. Nd4 Bd7
25. Bg2 Bc7 26. Nf3 Rad8 27. Rd2 Bc8 28. Rxd8 Rxd8 29. Rd1 Rg8 30. Bh3 Bd7 31.
Nh4 Bc6 32. Bg2 Be5 33. Bf3 Rg5 34. c3 Rg8 35. Re1 b5 36. Bd1 Bc7 37. Nf3 Bb7
38. Nd4 e5 39. Nc2 Bd6 40. Bf3 Rc8 41. a3 a5 42. Kb1 Bb8 43. Ne3 Ba7 44. Nd5+
Bxd5 45. exd5 b4 46. axb4 axb4 47. cxb4 Bd4 48. Rc1 Rxc1+ 49. Kxc1 Bg1 50. h3
Bf2 51. g4 Be1 52. b5 Ba5 53. Kc2 Kd6 54. Kd3 Kc5 55. d6 Kxd6 56. Kc4 Bb6 57.
b4 Bf2 58. Be4 Bb6 59. Bc2 Bf2 60. Bb1 Bb6 61. Be4 Bf2 62. Bf3 Bb6 63. Kd3 Bf2
64. Be4 Bb6 65. Ke2 Bd4 66. Kf3 Bc3 67. b6 Bxb4 68. b7 Kc7 69. Ke2 Bc5 70. Kd3
Bf2 71. Kc4 Be1 72. Kb5 Bf2 73. Ka6 Kb8 74. Bd5 Bd4 75. Bxf7 e4 76. Bd5 e3 77.
Bf3 Be5 78. h4 Bg3 79. g5 fxg5 80. hxg5 {1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

