{[%evp 0,94,34,26,46,46,51,51,11,11,51,41,39,46,68,55,60,45,29,4,45,20,20,21,
36,0,-8,5,26,-27,2,-5,27,-2,47,54,33,11,16,-1,6,5,0,-2,13,-14,22,-14,-13,-18,
-9,-47,-5,-57,-24,-48,-50,-42,0,-138,-52,-33,-33,-62,-107,-102,-98,-139,-139,
-162,-94,-184,-176,-176,-155,-259,-230,-254,-281,-305,-318,-310,-310,-345,-348,
-343,-327,-332,-259,-301,-301,-486,-486,-29993,-29994,-29995,-29996] Now, we
shall see how the great Rauzer expert GM Kozul sacrifices the f6-pawn in order
to get an endgame with a bishop pair.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Kb1
Qb6 {[%cal Bb6d4,Bh7h5]} 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. f5 h5 14. fxe6 fxe6 15. Qf4 Qc5 16.
Qxf6 Qe5 17. Qxe5 (17. Qf2 Bg7 {[%csl Bg7][%cal Bb5b4,Bg7a1]}) 17... dxe5 {
[%csl Rg2][%cal Gh5h4,Gh8g8,Gf8c5,Gb5b4,Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Ga4a3] Black has the
bishop pair and the counterplay on g-pawn which gives sufficient compensation
for a pawn. Zdenko Kozul who is considered as the most important specialist of
this variation and after whom this variation is named played this position
twice and interestingly enough none of the games resulted in a draw. This fact
proves the richness of the position and shows that both sides can play for a
win.} 18. Bd3 {White now chooses to continue his development without losing
time with the a3 move that we have seen in the game Volokitin, A-Kozul, Z 2005.
} (18. a3 {Black has many interesting choices in this position} Bc5 {Kozul
preferred the most natural developing move.} (18... b4 19. axb4 Bxb4 20. Na2
Bc5 21. Nc1 $1 (21. Bd3 a5 $1 22. Nc1 a4 $132 {Black has a good game.}) 21...
Ke7 22. Bd3 Rag8 23. Nb3 Bb6 $44) (18... Rb8 $5 {is interesting alternative.
Black wants to play ...b4.} 19. Bd3 (19. b4 a5 20. Na2 Bxe4 21. Re1 Bd5 22.
Rxe5 h4 $44) 19... b4 20. axb4 Bxb4 21. Kc1 (21. Na2 Ba3 22. b3 a5 $36 {
Black has a dangerous initiative.}) (21. Ne2 Ke7 $44) 21... Bxc3 22. bxc3 a5
$44 {Black is ready to play ...Ke7, ...a4. Black has good compensation.}) (
18... h4 $5 {is also possible.}) 19. Be2 Ke7 {Black intends to play ...h4 and
fixing the g2-pawn as a weakness.} 20. h4 {Volokitin, prevents Black's ...h4
idea by playing h4 himself and fixing a weak pawn on h5 to exploit this
advantage.} Bd4 $6 (20... Rag8 $1 {would be better.} 21. Bf3 a5 22. Ne2 b4 23.
axb4 axb4 24. Nc1 Rb8 25. Nd3 Bd4 26. Nf4 Rhg8 27. Ne2 (27. Nxh5 $2 b3 28. c3
Bc5 $19 {Black is planning to play ...Ra8-a2 and ...Rga8. White has no good
defence.}) 27... Bc5 $44 {Black has good compensation.}) 21. Bf3 Bxc3 22. bxc3
$14 {White is playing for two results here (win or draw). This riskless
position is very easy to play with White pieces. However, it is difficult to
say this for Black. Of course, Black has drawing chances but it is not easy to
play for a draw during the whole game. As we shall see in the game Volokitin
gradually increases his advantage.} Be8 (22... Raf8 23. Rd3 Rf4 24. Re3 $14)
23. Rd3 Rf8 24. Rhd1 Rf4 25. g3 Rf8 26. Kb2 $16 {Now White is clearly better
and Volokitin won this endgame by showing a very good technique.} Rc8 27. Kb3
a5 28. R1d2 Rg8 29. Be2 a4+ 30. Kb2 Rc7 31. Re3 Rh8 32. Rd1 Rb7 33. Rg1 Rb8 34.
Kc1 Bc6 35. g4 Rbg8 36. Reg3 hxg4 37. Rxg4 Rxg4 38. Rxg4 Be8 39. h5 $1 Kf6 (
39... Rxh5 $2 40. Rg7+ Kf6 41. Bxh5 $18) 40. Rg3 Rh7 41. Kd2 Bxh5 42. Bxb5 Bg6
43. Re3 Rh4 44. Kd3 Rh1 45. c4 $18 Rd1+ 46. Kc3 Rd4 47. Bc6 Ke7 48. Kb4 Kd6 49.
Kb5 Bh5 50. c3 Rd2 51. Kb6 Ra2 52. c5+ Ke7 53. c4 Rb2+ 54. Bb5 Rb3 55. Re1 Be8
56. c6 Rxa3 57. c7 {1-0 (57) Volokitin,A (2679)-Kozul,Z (2591) Sarajevo 2005})
18... Bc5 19. Ne2 Rg8 20. g3 (20. Ng1 Rxg2 21. Nf3 Bb7 22. Nxe5 O-O-O $44 {
Black has a great compensation.}) 20... Ke7 21. Rhf1 Raf8 22. a3 Bf2 $5 {
Kozul gets a chance to employ a similar idea to the wonderful 24. Ba7!! that
we have seen in one of the most important classical games Karpov,
Anatoly-Unzicker,Wolfgang 1974. Black intends to play ...h4. With this move,
we see the importance of studying classical games once again.} 23. Nc1 h4 24.
gxh4 Rg4 $5 (24... Bxh4 25. Rxf8 Rxf8 26. Rg1 Kd6 $44 {is also good.}) 25. Nb3
(25. h5 Rh4 26. Rd2 Bb6 27. Rxf8 Kxf8 28. b4 (28. Be2 Bxe4 29. Rd6 Bd4 30. Rxe6
Rxh2 31. Rxa6 Ke7 32. Ra5 Kd6 33. Rxb5 Be3 34. Rb3 Bxc1 35. Bd3 Bd5 36. c4 Bf3
37. Kxc1 e4 38. Bc2 Kc5 39. Rb8 e3 40. b4+ Kxc4 41. Rc8+ Kd4 42. Rd8+ Kc4 43.
Rc8+ {Draw with perpetual check.}) 28... Ke7 29. Nb3 Rxh5 $44 {Black will play
...Rh4 next and has a very good compensation.}) 25... Rxh4 26. Rd2 Rhf4 27. Re2
(27. Rfd1 Rh8 $44) 27... Be8 $1 {A very nice manoeuvre} 28. c4 Bb6 29. Rh1 $2 (
29. Rxf4 exf4 30. c5 Bc7 31. Rf2 Be5 $15 {Black has a slight advantage in this
endgame.}) (29. Rfe1 Bf2 30. Rf1 bxc4 $1 31. Bxc4 a5 $15 {Black wants to play .
..a4.} 32. Nxa5 $2 Bb6 33. Rxf4 exf4 34. Nb3 f3 $17) 29... Rf3 $2 (29... bxc4
$1 {This move would immediately finish the game.} 30. Bxc4 Bh5 $19) 30. Nc1 Be3
31. Na2 $2 {After this mistake, Black is clearly better.} (31. Rd1 Rh3 $132)
31... Bh6 $1 {It is difficult to play these worse positions without making
mistakes. White gets into a hopeless position by committing consecutive
mistakes.} 32. Kc2 $2 (32. Bc2 bxc4 $17 {Black is clearly better.}) 32... Bh5
$1 33. Rhe1 Rd8 34. Nb4 Rc8 35. Rg2 $2 (35. c5 Rxc5+ 36. Kb1 a5 37. Na6 Rc8 38.
Rc2 Rxc2 39. Bxc2 Bd2 40. Rg1 Be3 $17 {Black has a strong bishop pair and
clearly better position.}) 35... bxc4 36. Bf1 (36. Be2 Re3 $19 {White is
collapsed.}) 36... Rf4 37. Nxa6 Bf3 38. Rg3 Bxe4+ 39. Kc3 Bf5 $19 {Black will
play ...Rf2 next and White has a hopeless position.} 40. Rd1 Rf2 41. Rg2 Rf3+
42. Kb4 Rb3+ 43. Ka5 Be3 44. Nb4 Bd4 45. Rdd2 c3 46. bxc3 Rxa3+ 47. Kb5 Rb8+ {
0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

