{Now, we will examine a fresh example featuring the topic "pawn sacrifice for
an endgame with a bishop pair". In this position, Black's situation looks
critical. White attacks on a8 and f7. At the same time, there is no safe
shelter for the black king. The Iranian GM, however, finds an amazing resource
-} 17... Nxc4 $1 18. Qxa8+ Bd8 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gc4a3] It turns out that Black has
tremendous compensation for the exchange. For White is difficult to defend
against the threats of ...Bc6 and ...Na3.} 19. Qd5 Ne3 20. Qxd6 Nxd1 {[%csl
Bd7,Bd8] As often happens in Sicilian positions, the bishop pair provides
enough compensation for the pawn.} 21. Rxd1 $2 {Strangely enough, this move is
already a decisive mistake. As we know, Black is more than happy to play an
endgame.} ({White should have played} 21. Qxd1 {when after} h4 22. Ne2 a5 $44 {
Black still enjoys a decent compensation.}) 21... Qxd6 22. Rxd6 Bb5 {[%csl Bg3,
Bf3][%cal Ge8e7,Gh5h4,Gd8b6] Black is planning to follow with ... h5-h4, ...
Ke7, and ...Bb6. The white knights cannot get good squares and Black enjoys an
overwhelming advantage.} 23. Rd1 h4 24. Nf1 Bb6 25. N1d2 (25. Kc1 h3 $19) 25...
Bf2 $19 {[%csl Bg2,Bf3,Bd2][%cal Bh8g8,Bg8g2] Planning ...Rg8 and .. .Rxg2.
Black is already winning.} 26. b3 Rg8 27. Nc4 Rxg2 28. Rd2 h3 29. Kb2 Ke7 30.
Rd3 Ba7 31. a4 bxa3+ 32. Kxa3 Rxc2 33. Kb4 Re2 *

[Event "EU-chT 04th Final"]
