{[%evp 0,52,22,22,60,48,46,13,13,28,31,40,40,43,43,21,38,32,64,28,30,16,30,13,
-1,5,9,8,8,-9,14,-10,26,16,-31,13,15,21,16,24,16,11,5,-5,28,10,3,-12,16,9,7,0,
10,0,0] The combined pressure on e4 and g2 is another major idea in Rauzer
endgames. As we will see in the next example. even massive simplifications
does not solve White's problems. The first instructive moment arises on move
12.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 Bd7 7. Qd2 a6
8. O-O-O b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. f4 e6 11. f5 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 {[%csl Ge5,Gf8]} Bh6+
$1 {[%cal Gh6f4,Gf4e5] The reader is already familiar with this typical
manoeuvre. Black is planning to transfer the bishop to e5 via f4.} 13. Kb1 Bf4
14. Ne2 Be5 15. Qe3 Qc7 $1 {[%cal Ge8e7,Gb5b4,Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Ga4a3,Gc7c5] Black
wants to force the transition into an endgame with ...Qc5. Even if White
avoids the exchange of the queens, Black can start advancing his queenside
pawns, thus creating attacking chances.} 16. Nd4 Qc5 17. Qd2 Qxd4 $1 {Radulov
immediately takes the opportunity to enter a favourable endgame.} 18. Qxd4 Bxd4
19. Rxd4 Ke7 {[%csl Re4,Rg2][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] This is another typical endgame
that every Rauzer player should know. Even though Black does not enjoy a
bishop pair, he has an advantage since White is overextended. The typical idea
is to combine the pressure on e4 and g2. For that purpose, Black usually
advances his h-pawn all the way to h4, thus fixing the g2-pawn. At the same
time, the e4-pawn can be easily attacked with ...Bc6. Very often, in order to
win, Black needs to create a weakness even on the queenside. Gaining space on
the queenside and eventually fixing the a2-pawn is a thematic way to achieve
this goal.} 20. fxe6 {Sooner or later, White will be forced to play this move.
Otherwise, he should always reckon with ...exf5.} fxe6 21. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3,
Gh1d1] White would like to stabilize the position by playing simple moves such
as Bf3 and Rhd1. I find Black's next move to be very instructive -} e5 {
[%csl Gd6,Gd7,Re4,Ge5,Gf6] Fixing the e4-pawn. In positions without knights on
the board, you shouldn't fear weakening the d5-square. As strange as it may
seem, the exchange of the bishops will increase Black's winning chances. The
reason is simple. Even though the e2-bishop is theoretically bad, it is very
good at providing stability by defending the pawns on e4 and g2. In a rook
endgame, however, in order to develop these pawns, White will have to
sacrifice the activity of his rooks. With his last move, Radulov prepares the
eventual exchange of the bishops via g4-square.} ({Another possibility would
have been} 21... Rhg8 22. Bf3 e5 23. Rd2 Bg4 $15) 22. Rd3 {[%csl Bd7,Be2][%cal
Be2f3] Let's take a look at what can happen in a rook endgame.} Be6 ({In the
game Radulov played} 22... Bc6 $6 {which is a step in the wrong direction. 1/2
(95) -1/2 The game is a draw.}) 23. Rhd1 Bc4 24. R3d2 Bxe2 25. Rxe2 {[%csl Gd6,
Re4,Gf6,Rg2][%cal Gg8g2,Gc8c2] You can now see the tremendous difference in
the activity of the rooks. Black can put pressure along the semi-open files
"c" and "g". At the same time, the white rooks lack good prospects. The pawns
on d6 and f6 can be easily defended. These pawns are actually useful since
they reduce the scope of the white rooks.} h5 {[%csl Be4,Be5][%cal Be7e6,Bd6d5,
Bf6f5,Gh5h4]} 26. Red2 Rad8 $15 {[%cal Gh8g8,Gh5h4,Ge7e6,Gg8g4,Gd6d5,Gf6f5]
Black has an obvious advantage in this endgame. He has the following plan at
his disposal: 1) fixing the g2-pawn with ...h5-h4 2) forcing White's rook into
passive positions by playing ...Rhg8-g4 3) creating a passed pawn on e5 by
means of ...Ke6 followed by ...d6-d5 or ...f6-f5 4) combining the advance of
the passed pawn with the attack on the kingside weaknesses.} 1/2-1/2

