{[%evp 0,116,14,36,58,49,86,75,70,50,50,33,53,53,79,51,67,52,37,54,41,32,32,3,
5,18,30,7,59,62,43,-11,34,20,15,37,34,7,5,-36,-28,-7,6,29,29,4,37,-78,-78,-139,
-163,-163,-172,-169,-224,-188,-135,-127,-152,-177,-157,-144,-147,-190,-190,
-193,-156,-200,-162,-171,-155,-166,-107,-103,-53,-45,-55,-58,-44,-44,-52,-25,
15,15,42,0,157,-258,62,-167,-212,-263,-131,-251,-49,-49,-60,-75,-83,-94,-61,
-104,-72,-129,-129,-129,-118,-115,-142,-167,-213,-172,-238,-227,-312,-340,-340,
-353,-428] In Rauzer structures, one should know very well when the advance ...
e6-e5 works. We can formulate the following general advise: You should play ...
e6-e5 when none of white knights can reach the d5-square. That's why Black
often first chases the c3-knight away by playing ...b5-b4 and only then
proceeds with ...e6-e5. In the following example, Black managed to achieve a
classical Rauzer win.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6.
Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 {This is one of the main
tabiyas of the so-called Kozul Variation.} 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Qe3 Qe7 $1 {
[%csl Gc5][%cal Ge7e3,Gf4f5,Ge6f5,Ge7a7,Ga7c5,Gb5b4,Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Ga4a3]
Remember this thematic move. Black prepares the typical maneuver ...Qa7-c5
followed by the advance of the queenside pawns.} 13. Bd3 b4 14. Ne2 Qa7 15. Qh3
h5 $1 {Of course, the h5-square shouldn't be available for the white pieces.}
16. Rhe1 Qc5 17. Kb1 a5 18. f5 {[%cal Ge2f4] We have a thematic Rauzer
position. White is planning to increase the pressure on e6 by Nf4. How should
Black react?} e5 $1 {[%csl Re2] Of course! Since the e2-knight can never reach
d5, this advance is perfectly acceptable.} 19. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f1,Gf1e3] White
is now trying to reroute the knight via f1. This idea, however, does not work
quite well.} h4 20. Nf1 Ke7 21. Nd2 {White changes his initial intention.} ({
After} 21. Ne3 Bh6 22. Nd5+ Bxd5 23. exd5 {[%csl Bh6,Bd3,Bf5,Bd5,Bd4,Bd7][%cal
Ba5a4,Ba4a3,Bh6e3,Be7d7,Bh6f8,Bf8e7,Be7d8,Bd8b6,Bb6d4] We get a typical
position with opposite-coloured bishops. In such cases, Black's bishop has
much better prospects than its white counterpart. There is not a single square
where the white bishop will be active. On the other hand, in many cases, Black
can transfer his bishop to d4 and then proceed with his queenside attack. We
will take a look at similar positions in the next examples.}) 21... a4 22. Bc4
Bh6 23. Bd5 {White wants to provoke ...Bxd5 in order to free to e4-square for
the knight. Of course, Black will not play into White's hand.} Rac8 24. Bxc6
Rxc6 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Rd2,Gd5][%cal Gc8c2] We have a classical position in which
Black's dark-squared bishop dominates the white knight.} 25. Qd3 Rhc8 26. Rc1
a3 $1 {A typical way to weaken the c3-square.} 27. b3 Qc3 28. Qxc3 Rxc3 {
You should always have this endgame in your mind when playing the Rauzer. In
such structures, the c3-square is an invasion springboard for the black rooks.
White is already losing material.} 29. Re2 Bxd2 30. Rxd2 Re3 31. Rf1 Rxe4 $19 {
With a decisive advantage.} 32. Kc1 Re3 33. Kd1 Rec3 34. Rff2 R8c5 35. Rfe2 d5
36. Rd4 e4 37. Rxb4 Kd6 38. Ra4 Ke5 39. Rxa3 d4 40. Ra7 e3 41. Rxf7 Kxf5 42.
Rd7 Kg5 43. Rh7 f5 44. g3 hxg3 45. hxg3 Kg4 46. Rh4+ Kf3 47. Rxd4 Kxg3 48. Rd8
f4 49. Rg8+ Kf3 50. Rh2 Rc8 51. Rg7 R3c7 52. Rg6 Rd7+ 53. Kc1 Re8 54. Rh3+ Ke4
55. Rg2 Ree7 56. Rgh2 f3 57. Rh4+ Kd5 58. Rh1 e2 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

