{This position was reached in the game Orkhan Abdulov - Gadir Guseinov. Black
should decide how to deal with the pressure on e6. Since the white knight is
far away from the d5-square, the best move is} 16... e5 $1 {[%csl Rb1,Re2]
[%cal Ge8e7,Gb6c5,Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Ga4a3] The reader should be already familiar
with Black's plan in such positions. After putting the queen on c5 and the
king on e7, Black can start advancing his queenside pawns.} 17. Ng3 h4 18. Nh5
Bg5 {[%csl Gf6,Gg5,Gh4,Rh5] Remember this position. The construction Bg5 and
pawns on f6 and h4 is very effective against a knight on h5.} 19. g4 hxg3 20.
hxg3 Ke7 21. g4 a5 22. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4d5]} Qe3 $1 {Guseinov seizes the
opportunity to enter a favourable endgame.} 23. Bd5 Qxe1 24. Rhxe1 Rac8 25.
Bxc6 {[%csl Be4,Bg4]} Rxc6 {[%csl Rc2,Re4,Gg5,Rh5][%cal Gh8c8,Gc6c4] Once
again we can see how the dark-squared bishop dominates White's knight. The
weakness of the d5-square is not relevant since White cannot use it.} 26. Re2
Rhc8 27. Rd3 Rc4 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ba4a3,Gd6d5,Gc8c5,Ga5a3,Ga5a4] An important
typical position. In general, there are two typical ways to win this endgame
with Black. In the previous example, we have seen the invasion via the
important c3-square. In order to execute this idea, Black needs to start with .
..a5-a4-a3. Another very common approach is putting pressure on the 4th rank.
After putting his rook on c4, Black is planning to proceed with ...R8c5
followed by ...d6-d5. In such a case, he is going to collect the important
g4-pawn.} 28. a3 {White tries to create some kind of counterplay.} ({In case of
} 28. Rd1 {Black will follow with} R8c5 {[%cal Gd6d5] preparing the thematic ..
.d6-d5.}) 28... bxa3 29. Rxa3 d5 $6 {This move is an inaccuracy.} ({More to
the point would have been} 29... a4 {[%cal Gc8c5,Gd6d5] followed by ...R8c5.
Black has a big advantage.}) 30. exd5 a4 31. b3 axb3 $2 {After this mistake,
White's counterplay is enough for a draw.} ({Black should have played} 31...
Rxg4 $1 32. Rxa4 Rxa4 33. bxa4 Kd6 $15 {with slightly better chances. The
e5-pawn is an important asset in this position.}) 32. Ra7+ Kf8 33. cxb3 Rxg4
34. Ra6 Rg1+ 35. Kb2 Bc1+ 36. Ka2 Be3 37. b4 Bd4 38. Rc6 Ra8+ 39. Kb3 Rb1+ 40.
Kc4 Ra4 41. Rc8+ Ke7 42. Rc7+ Kd6 43. Rc6+ Kd7 44. Nxf6+ Kd8 45. d6 Rbxb4+ 46.
Kd5 Ba7 47. Ne4 Ra5+ 48. Nc5 Rbb5 49. Rc2 e4 50. Rh2 $4 (50. Rg2 $1 Rxc5+ 51.
Rxc5 Rxc5+ (51... Bxc5 52. Kc6) 52. Kxe4 $11) 50... Rxc5+ 51. Rxc5 Bxc5 52. Kc6
Bd4 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

