{Now, we shall take a brief look at a fragment taken from the game Rosko, L -
Michalik, P. White has just played the thematic f4-f5 advance. In the future,
he is planning to increase the pressure on e6 by means of g2-g3 followed by
Bh3. Black, however, has an excellent resource at his disposal -} 13... b4 $1 {
Chasing the knight away from the d5-square.} 14. Ne2 e5 $1 {Now, the white
knight cannot reach the key d5-square. Generally speaking, the sequence ...
b5-b4 followed by ...e6-e5 is very typical in Rauzer structures.} 15. Ng3 {
[%cal Gg3h5]} h5 $1 {One more thematic move. We shouldn't let the knight on h5.
} 16. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4d5]} h4 17. Nf1 Qc5 18. Bd5 Bxd5 {Now, White has a choice.
Since we are currently examining positions with weakness on d5, we are going
to focus on the move} 19. Qxd5 ({The game followed} 19. exd5 {when after} Bh6
20. Qe2 Rc8 21. g4 a5 $17 {[%csl Rf1,Gh6][%cal Ga5a4,Ga4a3] Black had a
considerable advantage.} 22. Qd3 Qc4 23. h3 O-O 24. Nh2 e4 25. Qxc4 Rxc4 26.
Rhe1 a4 27. Nf1 Rfc8 28. Re2 a3 29. b3 Rc3 30. Rd4 Rf3 31. Nd2 Bxd2 32. Rexd2
e3 33. Rd1 e2 34. Rc1 Re8 {0-1 White resigns.}) 19... Qxd5 20. Rxd5 {[%cal
Gf1e3,Ge3c4] White is planning to increase the pressure with Ne3-c4 followed
by Rhd1. Therefore, a key resource would be} Bh6 $1 {[%csl Bd6] Once again,
the d6-pawn is not important. Activity and development are what matters.} 21.
Nd2 ({Taking the pawn is a mistake -} 21. Rxd6 $2 Ke7 22. Rd1 Rhd8 $1 23. Re1
Rac8 $1 {[%cal Bd8d4,Bc8c4,Ba6a5,Ba5a4,Ba4a3] White is lost in this position
since he can hardly move. Black can either take the e4-pawn by putting his
rooks on d4 and c4 or first weaken the opponent's kingside with ...a6-a5-a4-a3.
}) 21... Rg8 $15 {Black is already better due to the annoying pressure on g2.
As usually happens in such positions, the knight lacks good squares.} *

