{[#] Now, we shall take a look at another very important type of Rauzer
endgames - positions with opposite-coloured bishops. The first example is
taken from the practice of GM Jaan Ehlvest. White's pressure on e6 forces
Black to take a decision. Ehlvest opts for the best solution -} 21... e5 ({
A typical mistake would be} 21... Bd7 $2 {when after} 22. Bc4 e5 23. Nd5 {
White is dominating.}) 22. Nd5 Bxd5 23. exd5 {[%csl Rc6,Rd3,Ge5,Ge7,Rf5,Rg2]
[%cal Ba4a3,Ge7d8,Gd8b6,Gb6d4,Ga5a3,Ga5a4,Ge8e7,Ga8g8,Gg8g5] This is another
very important type of position that you should know. Visually, both bishops
are quite bad. Such an impression, however, is an illusion. It's important to
evaluate the long-term potential of the bishops. While the d3-bishop can never
be activated (even on c6 it would be useless), its black counterpart has a
bright future. The target square is d4. Therefore, the manoeuvre...Bd8-b6-d4
is very thematic for such positions. Even if the bishop cannot reach the
d4-square, it is very active on the a7-g1 diagonal. Besides his queenside
attacking ideas with ... a5-a4-a3, Black will also put pressure on the pawns
g2 and f5. That's why you can often see the maneuver ...Ke7 followed by ...
Rag8-g5.} Bd8 $1 {Black starts rerouting the bishop.} 24. Rhf1 Kf8 25. Bb5 Rb8
26. Ba4 {White wants to prevent the advance of the black queenside pawns. Such
a defence, however, is quite passive.} Bb6 27. Rf3 Ke7 28. Rf4 {[%cal Gf4c4,
Gc4c6] Planning Rf4-c4 but allowing} Qe3 $1 {As we know, Black is doing fine
in almost all queenless positions.} 29. Re4 Qxe2 30. Rxe2 {[%csl Ra4] It
becomes clear That White is practically a piece down. The a4-bishop cannot be
activated.} Rh5 {[%csl Rf5,Rg2][%cal Gb8g8] Black starts applying his thematic
pressure on f5 and g2.} 31. Rf1 Bc5 32. Rf3 Rg8 {[%csl Bf5][%cal Bg8g5] It
turns out that White cannot defend his kingside. Ehlvest is planning to follow
with ...Rgg5.} 33. a3 bxa3 34. bxa3 Rgg5 $19 {Black is winning. After taking
the f5-pawn, he will start advancing his central pawns.} 35. Rb3 Rxf5 36. Rb8
Rf1+ 37. Ka2 f5 {[%cal Be7f6]} 38. Ra8 Rg5 39. Rxa5 Rg3 40. Rxc5 dxc5 41. Rxe5+
Kd6 42. Re8 Kxd5 43. Rd8+ Ke5 44. Bc6 Kf4 45. Rd2 Re1 46. a4 Re6 47. Bd7 Rf6
48. Bb5 Ke3 49. Rd3+ Kf2 50. Rd2+ Ke3 51. Rd3+ Kf2 52. Rd2+ Kg1 53. a5 Rxg2 54.
Rxg2+ Kxg2 55. a6 Rxa6+ 56. Bxa6 f4 57. Kb3 f3 58. Kc4 f2 59. Kxc5 Kxh3 60. Kd4
Kg2 61. Ke3 h3 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

