{The next example illustrates what can happen when both players play optimally.
Black should decide how to handle the annoying central tension. The readers
who have carefully followed the previous examples will easily find the right
decision. Kozul played} 16... Bxd5 $1 17. exd5 e5 {Black managed to obtain the
desirable position with opposite-coloured bishops. Compared to the previous
example, however, White is much more active in this position. Nevertheless, as
we will see, static factors matter a lot in this position.} 18. Bb5+ Ke7 19.
Bc6 {The bishop is not that threatening on c6. Usually, Black plays around
this bishop.} Qb6 20. Qe3 $5 {I am not sure whether White should have forced
the transition into an endgame.} ({An interesting alternative would have been} 
20. Re4 $5 {keeping more tension in the position.}) 20... Qxe3 21. Rxe3 Bh6 {
[%csl Rf5,Rg2][%cal Gh5h4,Gh8g8,Gg8g5]} 22. Re2 Rb8 {This move is not at all
forced. Kozul is fighting against the advance a2-a3.} ({More to the point
would have been} 22... Rhg8) ({or} 22... Rcg8) 23. Rd3 h4 {Fixing the g2-pawn.}
({Even more precise would have been} 23... Rhg8 $1 {[%cal Gg8g5] when the game
might continue} 24. a3 Rg5 25. Rf2 h4 26. Ka2 Rg4 {[%csl Gb4,Rg2,Gg4][%cal
Gb8g8]} 27. Rb3 Rbg8 $15 {[%csl Rg2] Black is already slightly better.}) 24. a3
$1 {[%cal Gb1a2,Ga2b3,Gb3c4,Ga3b4,Ga5b4,Gd3b3] This is White's thematic way to
handle the endgame. He should quickly organize the queenside counterplay. The
idea of the last move is axb4 followed by Ka2-b3-c4 and Rb3. This plan,
however, is time-consuming.} Bf4 25. g3 hxg3 26. hxg3 Bg5 27. Ka2 Kf8 28. axb4
({The immediate} 28. Kb3 {will be answered with} Bc1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb4a3]
putting an annoying pressure on b2.} 29. a4 Rh1 $15 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf8e7,
Gb8h8] Black is already better since White's queenside activity has been
estinguished.}) 28... axb4 29. Kb3 Kg7 $6 {Even though this move does not
change the overall evaluation of the endgame, it seems a bit slow.} ({More
dynamic would be} 29... Rh1 30. Kc4 Rf1 31. Rb3 Rxf5 32. Rxb4 Rxb4+ 33. Kxb4 {
when the arising double-edged endgame seems to be equal. The following lines
are by no means forced. I provide them in order to illustrate the character of
the play.} Rf3 34. Kb5 Rxg3 35. Bd7 Ke7 36. Kc6 Rf3 37. c4 f5 38. c5 (38. b4
Rc3 39. c5 f4 40. Bf5 f3 41. Rc2 Rxc2 42. Bxc2 f2 43. Bd3 e4 44. Bf1 e3 45. Kb7
dxc5 46. bxc5 Bf4 47. Kc6 f5 48. d6+ Bxd6 49. cxd6+ Kd8 $11) 38... dxc5 39.
Rxe5+ Kf6 40. Re2 Rd3 $11) 30. Kc4 $5 Rh1 31. Rb3 Rf1 $2 {After this move,
White gets a considerable advantage.} ({The last chance was} 31... Bc1 {
[%csl Bb2,Bb3]} 32. c3 Rbh8 $1 33. Rxb4 R8h2 34. Rxh2 Rxh2 35. b3 Rc2 $11) 32.
Rxb4 Rxb4+ 33. Kxb4 Rxf5 34. Bd7 Rf3 35. g4 $1 $16 {[%csl Bf6,Be5][%cal Bc2c4,
Bb2b4]} Bc1 36. c3 Rf4+ 37. Kb3 Rf1 38. Bf5 (38. Kc2) 38... Kh6 39. Kc4 Kg5 40.
Kb5 Kf4 41. Re4+ Kf3 42. b4 Bd2 43. c4 Rc1 (43... Rb1 44. c5 $18) 44. c5 Bxb4
$1 45. c6 $1 (45. Kxb4 $2 Rxc5) 45... Bc5 46. Ka6 $18 Ra1+ 47. Kb7 Rb1+ 48. Kc8
Bb6 49. Kd7 Ra1 50. Rb4 Ra7+ 51. Kxd6 Bc7+ 52. Kc5 e4 53. Bxe4+ Kxg4 54. Rb7
1-0

