apart.} 17. Bd3 gxf4 18. Rf2 Bc5 $17 {The bishop pair is tremendously strong.}
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2021.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Rauzer Bg5"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B69"]
[Annotator "GM Boris Avrukh"]
[PlyCount "72"]
[EventDate "2019.??.??"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.12.05"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 (2... Nc6 {Although Black can go for the Rauzer via
different move orders, I find 2...d6 the most precise. My reasoning is that
after 2...Nc6 White can go for the Rossolimo which has turned into a reliable
weapon of White. After all, we even saw a whole 3 (!) games in it during the
Carlsen-Caruana 2018 World Championship match!} 3. Bb5) 3. d4 (3. Bb5+ {
is also a serious line that Black should be prepared for}) 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 (
4. Qxd4 {Another side line that is good to know}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 {We got
to the starting point of the famous Richter-Rauzer line: White has a couple
different options but the vast majority of games here continue with 6.Bg5. I
believe one advantage of the Rauzer is that it is not as heavy on theory as
the wildly popular Najdorf, for example.} 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O (8. Nxc6
bxc6 9. O-O-O Be7 $1 (9... d5 10. Qe3 {is the modern approach to this line
which I find rather promising for White} (10. e5 h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Nd7 13.
h4 g4 14. Qe2 Rg8 15. Qd3 Rb8 {0-1 (51) Morozevich,A (2730)-Avrukh,B (2633)
Turin 2006}) 10... Be7 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Bc4 $1 {with direct pressure on d5.
Additionally, the Bishop will go to b3 and ensure that the White king is safe
thus leaving Black without a lot of counterplay}) 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Bc4 (11. f4
d5 $1 {[%csl Gb2]}) 11... Bb7 12. Bb3 Qc7 13. f4 O-O-O $13 {is the difference
again since Black has the option to castle. The king is pretty safe since
Black has not made teh commitment of pushing b5 as in the Kozul line Black has
kept the flexibility of his structure and ensured that his king is safe.
Castling queenside is possible since he did not make the commitment of pushing
b5 earlier in the game}) 8... Bd7 {By far the top choice in the Rauzer these
days. Now, White has to settle on a plan: he has two main options which lead
to different structures and dynamics. The first one is a more flexible setup
with 9.f3 and the second one is the classical 9.f4. My personal impression is
that recently 9.f3 enjoys better popularity} (8... h6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bf4 d5
11. Qe3) 9. f4 (9. f3 {The other major alternative} Nxd4 (9... Be7 {was my
preferred system when I was facing this 15 years ago} 10. Be3 {[%cal Yg2g4,
Yh2h4] White is retreating the bishop to clear the path in front of the h and
g pawns} (10. h4 h6 11. Be3 h5 $14 {is discussed in my previous games}) (10. g4
h5 $1 $11 {Black takes on an active approach! Nowadays, h5 has become a
frequent guest in the Sicilian defense}) 10... h5 {is still considered theory.
However, I am not thrilled about this move as I do not want to include h5
before White has shown how he intends to advance the h and g pawns.}) 10. Qxd4
Be7 {Main line} ({A viable alternative is} 10... Bc6 {A possible downside of
the move though is that it closes the c file which Black would otherwise use
to create pressure} 11. h4 (11. e5 {always needs to be considerd as it is
White's main central break. In this version, it does not help White achieve
anything as illustrated by this correspondence game:} Qa5 $1 (11... dxe5 {
is also playable} 12. Qxe5 Nd7 13. Qg3 (13. Qe3 Bc5 $15) 13... Qb6 $146 14. Bd3
h6 15. Bf4 (15. Bd2 O-O-O (15... Bc5 16. Qxg7 Bd4 17. Qg3 O-O-O $44)) 15... Nf6
$13) 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. exd6 Qe5 14. d7+ Kd8 15. Qb6+ {Contora: '1/2-1/2 (19)
Elent,M (2455) -Voll,A (2571) ICCF email 2016'} Qc7 16. Qd4 Qe5) 11... h6 12.
Be3 Qc7 {Continuing development and not waiting for White to show his
intentions. Jumabayev decided not to rush with d5 but I believe it is at least
worth considering} (12... d5) 13. g4 $6 (13. Qd2 d5 $5 14. e5 Nd7 15. f4 h5 $13
) 13... d5 $1 {Now that White has weakened his kingside structure, there is no
better moment to break the center} 14. exd5 (14. g5 {0-1 (56) Khanin,S (2482)
-Jumabayev,R (2654) Lichess. org INT 2020} hxg5 15. Bxg5 dxe4 16. Nxe4 (16.
fxe4 Rd8) 16... Nxe4 17. fxe4 f6 18. Bd2 Rd8 (18... Bd6 {[%cal Gd6e5]}) 19. Qc3
Bd6 $17) (14. e5 $2 {demonstrates the idea of Bc6} Nd7 {[%cal Yf8c5,Yc6h1,
Yc5e3]} 15. f4 $4 Bc5 16. Qd2 d4 $19) 14... Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Be2 Rc8 $15
{At first glance, it seems that White is far ahead in development. A more
careful look though, shows that Black has more than enough time to coordinate
his pieces accordingly} 17. Rd2 {Contora: '1/2-1/2 (88) Muzychuk,M (2540)
-Jumabayev,R (2604) Caleta 2019'} Bd6 $1 $36 {with a great position due to the
active positions of the Black forces} 18. Qxg7 $140 $2 Be5 {[%csl Gg7]}) ({
another good option} 10... h6 11. Be3 (11. Bxf6 {only leaves Black with a
comfortable position. Going into an endgame with 11...Qf6 or keeping the
queens on board with 11...gxf6 are both good options} Qxf6 (11... gxf6 12. f4)
12. Qxf6 gxf6 $15) 11... Bc6 {with ideas similar to those in the direct 10...
Bc6 line}) 11. h4 (11. g4 h5 (11... O-O) 12. gxh5 (12. h4 hxg4 13. fxg4 b5 14.
Be2 Qb8 {[%cal Gb5b4]}) 12... Nxh5 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Black has a superior pawn
structure and all of his pieces have come into play: any forcing lines should
be in his favor} 14. Qxd6 $6 Qxd6 15. Rxd6 {Black is able to regain the
sacrificed material using the pin along the h file with 15...Ng3.
Consecutively, only Black can be better in this endgame as White has not fully
completed his development yet. While the computer might be holding this as
White, defending in a practical game would be very unpleasant.} Ng3 16. Rg1
Nxf1 17. Rxf1 Rxh2 $11) (11. Be3 O-O (11... h5 $5 12. Kb1 (12. Qb6 Qb8 13. Bf4
Bc6 14. Kb1 Nd7 15. Qe3 b5 $13) (12. Bg5 Qc7 13. f4 Bc6) 12... b5 13. h4 (13.
Qd2 {ctr f7}) 13... Qc7 14. Qd2 b4 15. Ne2 a5 16. Bg5 a4 17. Nf4 {0-1 (53)
Dominguez Perez,L (2758)-Shankland, S (2691) chess24. com INT 2020} Rb8 $13)
12. g4 Bc6 {[%cal Gf6d7,Rg4g5] Opening up the d7 square for the knight}) 11...
b5 12. Kb1 (12. g4 Qc7 (12... Qb8) (12... O-O 13. Kb1 Rc8 (13... Qa5 14. Ne2 (
14. a3 Rfb8 15. Na2 Qd8) 14... Rfc8 15. Ng3 (15. Qd2 Qxd2 16. Rxd2 $14 Bc6)
15... b4 16. Nh5 e5 17. Qd2 Be6 18. b3 Rc3 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Nxf6+ gxf6 21. Bd3
$16) (13... Qc7 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Qxd6 Qxd6 16. Rxd6 Rfd8 17. a3 Be5 18. Rd1
Bc6 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Bd3 $14) (13... Rb8 14. Qd2 b4 15. Ne2 a5 16. Be3 a4 17.
g5 Ne8 18. h5 Qc8 19. Ka1 a3 20. b3 f5 21. exf5 Rxf5 22. f4 $14) 14. a3 Rb8 (
14... Qa5 15. Bd2 Qc7 16. h5 d5 17. exd5 Bc5 18. Qd3 Nxd5 19. Nxd5 exd5 20.
Qxd5 Rfe8 21. h6 g6 22. Bc3 Be6 23. Qg5 Be7 24. Qe5 Qxe5 25. Bxe5 $14) 15. Bxf6
gxf6 16. g5 Bc6 17. gxf6 Bxf6 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 $14) (12... Rb8 13. Kb1 b4
14. Ne2 a5 15. Ng3 O-O 16. Be3 a4 17. g5 Ne8 18. f4 Qc7 19. Rh2 Bb5 20. Rf2
Bxf1 21. Rdxf1 a3 22. f5 Rc8 23. Rg2 axb2 24. f6 Bd8 25. Qxb4 Rb8 26. Qa4 Qb7
27. h5 Ra8 28. Qb3 Qa6 29. Bd4 Bb6 30. Bxb6 Rb8 31. fxg7 Nxg7 32. Qf3 Rxb6 33.
a3 Rb7 34. g6 h6 35. Rd2 Qa5 36. Rd3 Rc7 37. Qf4 Qc5 38. Rf2 Nxh5 39. Nxh5 Qxh5
40. Qxd6 Qg5 41. gxf7+ Rcxf7 42. Rg3 Rxf2 43. Rxg5+ hxg5 44. Qg3 Rf1+ 45. Kxb2
Kf7 46. Qxg5 Rb8+ 47. Ka2 Rfb1 48. Qe5 R1b5 49. Qd4 R8b7 50. c4 Ra5 51. e5 Ra6
52. Qe4 Rba7 53. Qd3 Ke7 54. c5 Ke8 55. Kb2 Rb7+ 56. Kc2 Rc6 57. Qg6+ Kd8 58.
Qg8+ Kc7 59. Qf7+ Kb8 60. Qe8+ Rc8 61. Qxe6 Rxc5+ 62. Kd3 Rbb5 63. Kd4 {
1/2-1/2 (63) Bauer,M (2179)-Sikorsky,H (2186) GER email 2009}) 13. Be3 (13. Kb1
h5 14. gxh5 Nxh5 15. Rg1 (15. Rh2 Qc5) 15... Nf6) 13... Rb8 (13... O-O 14. h5 (
14. g5 Nh5) 14... e5 15. Qd2 b4 16. Ne2 (16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 f5) 16... h6 17.
g5 hxg5 18. Bxg5 Rfc8 19. Ng3 a5 20. Kb1 a4 21. Bd3 $40) 14. Ne2 (14. h5 b4 15.
Ne2 h6 16. Qd2 a5 17. Nd4 a4) 14... b4 15. Qd2 Bb5 16. Kb1 a5 17. Bh3 (17. g5
Nd7 (17... Nh5)) 17... a4 18. Nd4 Nd7 19. g5) 12... Qc7 {[%cal Yb5b4,Ya6a5,
Ya8b8] Delaying castling for a while so that our queenside initiative gains
momentum.} 13. Qd2 (13. g4 h5 14. gxh5 Nxh5 $14) 13... b4 14. Ne2 a5 15. g4 (
15. Nd4 O-O {here it is probably best castle and embrace the sharp struggle
that arises. Black's queenside attack is enough to give him counterplay}) 15...
h5 {hindering White's attack} 16. gxh5 Nxh5 17. Nd4 Rb8 18. Bh3 {0-1 (54)
Areshchenko,A (2652) -Demchenko,A (2645) Tbilisi 2017} (18. Rg1 Nf6 19. Bd3 e5
20. Ne2 a4 $132 {1/2-1/2 (76) Bilguun,S (2478) -Gupta,A (2606) Xingtai 2019})
18... a4 19. Rhg1 Nf6 $13) 9... Be7 (9... b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 {The Kozul
variation.Personally, I prefer to go for 9...Be7 as I believe 9...b5 does not
suit me very well. If interested in the line, I would recommend IM Ogulcan
Kanmazalp's course for Modern chess where he takes a deeper look at it} (10...
Qxf6 $2 {loses to} 11. e5)) 10. Nf3 b5 11. Bxf6 (11. e5 {has to be checked on
every move} b4 $1 {otherwise the game is simply over} 12. exf6 (12. exd6 $6
bxc3 13. Qxc3 Bf8 {Might appear scary but Black has enough tactical ideas to
keep him in the game} 14. Bc4 (14. f5 $2 Qa5 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qxf6 Rg8 $17 17.
fxe6 fxe6 18. Bc4 Bg7 19. Qh4 Rb8 20. Bb3 Qf5 $17 {0-1 (30) Burger, K-Mednis,E
New York, NY 1969}) 14... Rc8 (14... h6 15. Bh4 Qa5 16. Qd3 Nb4 17. Qb3 Rb8 18.
Ne5 Ne4 19. a3 Bxd6 20. Be1 Bxe5 21. fxe5 Ba4 $1 $17 (21... Na2+ $6 {0-1 (39)
Sengupta, D (2587)-Narayanan,S (2517) Runavik 2017})) 15. Bxa6 Rb8 $11 16. f5
$2 {0-1 (35) Ballester Llagaria,L (2331)-Balakrishnan,P (2498) Chess.com INT
2020} Ne4 $1 17. Qxc6 Nxg5 $19) 12... bxc3 13. Qxc3 gxf6 14. Bh4 {The main
position after 11.e5} (14. Rxd6 $4 {is a blunder due to} Bxd6 15. Bxf6 Bb4 $1
$19 {0-1 (21) Apryshko,G (2399)-Demchenko,A (2679) Sochi RUS 2018}) 14... d5 {
Even though I was intrigued by 15...Rg8, I settled for this more natural
approach. Black opens up his bishop and intends to follow with Rb8 and then
Rg8. I would like to stress once again that both lines are good which once
again asserts the wisdom: "If there are various good choices in the position,
we have nothing to worry about!"} (14... Rg8 $5 {is a new trend. The move has
been tested by both MVL and his second, the renowned theoritician, Etienne
Bacrot. Although the idea behind the move is simple- forcing White to protect
g2 and thus preventing the development of the light squared bishop- massive
complications follow.}) 15. Kb1 Rb8 16. a3 Rg8 {castling would just be asking
for trouble} 17. Bxa6 {In exchange for the pawn, Black gets open files against
the enemy king and sufficient compensation} Qb6 18. Bf1 Ra8 19. Qb3 Qa7 $11 20.
Qc3 Qb8 $1 $146 (20... Rb8 $6 {1-0 (38) Inarkiev,E (2692) -Gupta,A (2602)
Sharjah UAE 2019}) (20... Qb6 21. Qb3 Qa7 $11) 21. Qb3 Qxf4 22. Bg3 Qa4 23.
Qxa4 Rxa4 24. Bb5 Ra7 25. c4 Rb7 $1 26. Rd3 dxc4 27. Rxd7 Rxb5 28. Rc7 Nd8 $11)
11... gxf6 {In contrast to the Kozul variation, Black can opt for a queenside
castle in this position. As a reminder, Black never wants to take the pawn
when White pushes f5 since he would be essentially lost after giving up the d5
square.} (11... Bxf6 {has been played quite a few times in older games but to
me Black is just a pawn down without much compensation} 12. Qxd6 Be7 (12...
Bxc3 13. bxc3 $16) 13. Qd2 b4 14. Na4 Ra7 (14... Nb8 15. Qd4 $1 $16) 15. Qe3 $1
Qa5 16. b3 Rb7 17. Nd2 Na7 18. Nc4 Qc7 19. Rxd7 $1 Qxd7 20. Nc5 Bxc5 21. Qxc5
$44 {White has tremendous initiative for the exchange in Psakhis - Geller,
Moscow 1986.}) 12. Kb1 (12. f5 Qb6 (12... exf5 $2 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Bd3 $16)
13. Qh6 {is an aggressive move that also deserves attention.} (13. Kb1 {
transposition}) (13. Ne2 $6 {Re-routing the knight here would be a positional
mistake because it allows Black to trade queens with} Qa5 $1) (13. fxe6 fxe6
14. g3 {allows} b4 15. Ne2 Qf2 $1 {and once again it is hard to avoid the
queen exchange.}) 13... O-O-O 14. Qh5 Rhf8 (14... Be8 15. Bd3 (15. Qh3 Kd7)
15... Kb8 16. Rhe1 {theory}) 15. Qxh7 $6 Kb8 16. Qh4 Rc8 17. Kb1 Rc7 18. Qe1
Rfc8 $44 {The lack of the h7 pawn does not make a difference at the moment as
the play is on the queenside/center. Black has pressure over the c file, the
bishop pair and can further continue with b4, a5.}) 12... Qb6 13. f5 O-O-O 14.
g3 (14. Qh6 Kb8 {transposes to the above line} 15. Qh5 Rhf8 16. Bd3 (16. Qxh7 {
might end with a repetition chasing the queen if Black pleases:} b4 ({In case
Black is in a fighting spirit he could also try:} 16... Rc8 17. Qh6 Rc7 18. Bd3
Rfc8 {where such compensation is interesting. Depending on White's choice,
Black might continue Nb4, Ne5 or Na5.}) 17. Ne2 Rh8 18. Qxf7 Rdf8 $11) 16...
Na5) 14... Kb8 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Bh3 Na5 $1 {This relatively new move came up
in a 2018 game between strong GMs Le vs Gupta and offered a fresh perspective
of the position. The idea has turned into one of the main theoretical disputes
in the Rauzer these days and revived my interest in the line. Black actively
tries to take the initiative and, so far, his results look fine!} ({Back when
I was playing the line 16...Bc8 was considered the main move in the position.
Gradually, Black would try to push b4 and get the d5 break in the center
activating the dark squared bishop. However, the position bothered me since
after the most popular 17.Qe1, I believed White has lasting pressure on the
Black central pawns.} 16... Bc8 17. Qe1 (17. Ne2 $6 {allows} d5 $1 {which is
precisely the type of counterplay White needs to prevent}) 17... Rhe8 18. Rf1
$14) 17. Nd4 (17. b3 $5 {is another idea which has been tried. The motif
behind it is simple: allowing the knight to come to c4 is more dangerous than
the b3 weakening. Although it looks risky for White, computers say the move is
perfectly sound. Ah, how much our silicone friends have changed the game!} b4
18. Ne2 Nb7 {The knight has nothing to do on a5 after provoking b3. Therefore,
Black transfers it to a more active position} 19. Rhe1 {While analyzing I
stumbled on the following positional pawn sacrifice:} d5 $1 $146 (19... Nc5 {
has been played before. However, White enjoys a better position after 20.Nf4
where he applies continuous pressure to Black's center} 20. Nf4 $14 {[%cal
Yf3d4,Yf4e6,Yd4e6,Yh3e6] 1/2 (45)-1/2 (45) Yeletsky,I (2412)-Grachev,A (2277)
Ekaterinburg 2018}) 20. exd5 (20. e5 f5 $11) 20... e5 21. Bxd7 (21. Qh6 Nd6 22.
Ned4 exd4 23. Rxe7 Bxh3 24. Qxh3 Nb5 25. Kc1 Rxd5 $11) 21... Rxd7 22. Qd3 (22.
Nh4 Nd6 23. Rf1 Rhd8 24. Nf5 (24. Ng2 Nb5 $15 {[%cal Ge7c5,Gb5a3]}) 24... Nxf5
25. Rxf5 Rxd5 26. Qxd5 Rxd5 27. Rxd5 Qe6 $19) 22... Nd6 $1 {Surprisingly, the
knight switches directions and instead of c5 goes over to b5! The position is
very unbalanced and objectively White has everything to play for, but in a
real game I would prefer to play from Black's side because of the strong
initiative.} 23. Nh4 Rc8 24. Nf5 Nb5 $44) 17... b4 $1 18. Nce2 e5 19. Bxd7 {
It may seem that trading the light squared bishops favors White (because of
Black's weak pawn structure) but Black has lots of dynamics to compensate that}
(19. Nf5 Nc4 20. Qd3 Bxf5 21. Bxf5 Ne3 22. Be6 Nxd1 23. Rxd1 h5 $13) 19... Rxd7
20. Nf5 Nc4 21. Qd3 (21. Qd5 Rc8) 21... Rc8 {[%cal Yd6d5,Ye7c5,Ye7d8,Yd8b6] If
the White knight somehow manages to get to d5, as Black we would be
strategically lost: therefore we need to avoid such scenario at all costs.
Luckily, such maneuver is currently not possible! Black enjoys strong
counterplay on the queenside with a5, a4 and Na3 soon to follow. A key idea in
the position is sacrificing the d pawn to let our only problematic piece- Be7-
into play. If that is not possible, it might be activated via d8 and b6.} 22.
Nc1 {The most played move} a5 23. Nb3 (23. Rhe1 a4 24. Ne3 Nxe3 25. Qxe3 Qc6
26. Re2 a3 27. Rd5 axb2 28. Nd3 Rb7 29. Nxb2 Ra7 30. Qb3 Kc7 $1 $13 {[%cal
Gc7d7,Gc8a8]}) 23... d5 $5 {Initiative over material!} (23... Bf8 24. Nd2 Na3+
25. bxa3 Rc3 26. Qe2 bxa3+ 27. Nb3 a4 28. Rd5 Rb7 29. Rd3 Qc6 30. Rhd1 Rc7 31.
Ne3 axb3 32. Rxc3 Qxc3 33. cxb3 Bh6 34. Nc4 Rxc4 35. bxc4 Qb4+ 36. Ka1 Qc3+ $11
) 24. exd5 a4 25. Nxe7 $1 $146 {White cannot let the bishop become active as
that would likely result into coming under a strong attack} (25. Nd2 $2 {
is a tactical mistake as demonstrated by the strong Indian GM Sethuraman:} Na3+
26. bxa3 Rc3 27. Qe2 bxa3+ 28. Nb3 axb3 29. cxb3 Rxb3+ 30. Ka1 (30. axb3 Qxb3+
31. Ka1 Bb4 {Black's threats cannot be deflected} 32. Rd3 Bc3+ 33. Rxc3 Qxc3+
34. Ka2 Rxd5 35. Rb1+ Kc7 36. Rb3 Rd2+ $19) 30... Rb2 31. Rb1 Bb4 $19 {0-1 (36)
Zou,C (2440) -Sethuraman,S (2630) Changsha CHN 2019}) 25... Rxe7 26. d6 (26.
Nd2 Ne3 27. d6 (27. Rc1 Rd7 $17 {the pawn drops}) 27... Rd7 {transposition})
26... Rd7 27. Nd2 Na3+ 28. bxa3 bxa3+ 29. Nb3 Rc6 30. Qe2 Rdxd6 31. Rxd6 Rxd6
32. Rd1 Rxd1+ 33. Qxd1 axb3 34. axb3 e4 35. Qd5 e3 36. Qg8+ Kc7 $11 *

