1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 {While preparing my
lecture, I wanted to demonstrate the rich possibilities and different systems
which made the Rauzer one of my favorite openings. Additionally, I thought it
might be interesting to show how my Rauzer knowledge evolved over the years
and my current opinion on the lines. Therefore, I decided to start with one of
my early games from a world youth championship:} 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. O-O-O
Nxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. f4 Qa5 {The main move. The following line is often
regarded to as the Old Main Line} 11. Bc4 Bd7 12. e5 dxe5 13. fxe5 Bc6 14. Bd2
Nd7 15. Nd5 {We are still in deep theory- Black has two options to choose from,
even though one of them usually transposes into the other. Most of the games
here continue with 15...Qd8 but being 14 years old, I preferred to employ 15...
Qc5 hoping that my opponents would fall for the trap and play 16.Bb4? .
Unfortunately, it never happened...} Qc5 16. Nxe7+ (16. Bb4 $2 Bg5+ $19) 16...
Qxe7 17. Rhe1 Nb6 18. Bf1 Rfd8 19. Qg4 Qc5 20. Qb4 {White tries to exchange
the queens because an endgame would benefit him due to having the bishop pair}
Qg1 {Back in the time, I had analyzed this variation and come up with this
funny idea trying to create problems for White on the kingside. A curious fact
though was that during the game I had trouble recalling whether the move was
Qf2 or Qg1! However, when I recently checked the line with a computer, it
turned out that the engine does not share my enthusiasm and the position is
not in Black's favor at all!} 21. Qh4 Qc5 $14 {We are not going to look
further into the game since the lecture's main focus is on the opening/early
middlegame} 22. Kb1 Qd4 23. Qh5 Na4 24. Bc1 Qb4 25. Ka1 Rd5 26. Bd3 Rxd3 27.
cxd3 Bd5 28. Qe2 Nc5 29. b3 Rd8 30. Be3 Na6 31. Qb2 Qb5 32. Bg5 Rc8 33. Rc1 Bc6
34. Red1 Nb4 35. Qd4 h6 36. Be7 0-1

