1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 d6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Bg5 {One of the
reasons I like the Rauzer so much is that, in my opinion, anything besides the
6.Bg5 system does not pose significant problems to Black. I believe the side
lines here do not yield as much poison as opposed to, let's say, the Najdorf
where there are more tricky systems for White to choose from (e.g. 6.Be3, 6.
Bc4 etc.)} e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O h6 {I started to play this line after moving
to Israel and discussing it with some of the coaches there. We had thorough
analyses and overall I enjoyed great results. The line was gaining popularity
at the time which is demonstrated by the curious situation where I had
prepared a very interesting novelty- an exchange sacrifice- only to see it
being played in a tournament by none other than Vladimir Kramnik!} 9. Be3 (9.
Nxc6 {During one Israeli league, a GM teammate of mine came up to me saying he
had an interesting idea to discuss showing the following line:} bxc6 10. Bf4 d5
11. Qe3 $5 {Initially, I was sceptical of the idea and quickly dismissed it as
I did not fully realize how dangerous it is. Nevertheless, soon high-level
games started to appear in this line so I spent a lot of hours looking for a
comfortable continuation for Black. And there was not one I liked! Eventually,
because of 11.Qe3, I stopped playing the h6 line. But what is the idea behind
such a curious move? What is wrong with developing with normal moves such as
Be7, 0-0? Truth is, Black would be in great shape after those if it weren't
for h6 which helps White open up lines more easily after h4, g4-->g5. One more
drawback of h6 is that Black always needs to watch out for the potential
sacrifice Bxh6. A great game which shows the dangers Black faces here is 1-0
Karjakin- Ivanchuk (2016)} Be7 12. Be2 O-O 13. h4 {I had tried to come back to
the h6 line but even with the new theory developments I was still dissatisfied
with the position. Therefore, I switched to something else in the Rauzer: 7...
Qb6.}) 9... Be7 10. f3 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 12. Kb1 Rb8 13. Bd3 b4 14. Ne2 e5 15.
Ba7 Rb7 16. Bf2 Be6 17. Nc1 a5 18. g4 Nd7 19. h4 Qc7 20. Qe2 Rb8 21. Rdg1 g6
22. Rd1 Kf8 23. Nb3 Kg7 24. Nd2 Rhc8 25. b3 a4 26. Bc4 Ra8 27. Qd3 axb3 28.
cxb3 Qa5 29. Qc2 Nf6 30. g5 hxg5 31. hxg5 Nh5 32. Qb2 Qa3 33. Qxa3 Rxa3 34.
Bxe6 fxe6 35. Rc1 Rca8 36. Rc2 d5 37. Re1 Bxg5 38. exd5 exd5 39. Rxe5 Bf6 40.
Rxd5 Nf4 41. Rd7+ Kg8 42. Ne4 Rxb3+ 43. Kc1 Bc3 44. Bg3 Ne6 45. Re7 Ng7 46. Be5
Nf5 47. Nxc3 bxc3 48. Re6 Nh4 49. Bxc3 Rxa2 50. Rxa2 Rxc3+ 51. Kd2 Rxf3 52. Ra4
g5 1/2-1/2

