{[%evp 0,52,19,29,55,56,76,62,58,37,50,32,41,60,59,32,77,38,57,29,21,16,15,29,
14,23,11,-3,-12,-20,-29,-225,-153,-171,-171,-157,-157,-619,-591,-556,-495,-516,
-475,-746,-712,-742,-753,-808,-790,-826,-632,-693,-700,-700,-598]} 1. Nf3 c5 2.
e4 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Qb6 8. Nb3 {For some
reason, most of my opponents preferred 8.Nb3 over 8. Bxf6 so I adjusted and
employed another move order- 8...a6. waiting for them to castle queenside. The
point is that Black plays a useful move and delays Be7: the reasoning is that
after 9.0-0-0 and only then 9...Be7, Bxf6 is no longer dangerous for Black. On
the other hand, if White plays 8.Bxf6, Black is happy because he has not lost
a tempo for Be7} a6 9. O-O-O Be7 10. f3 {A logical way for White to continue
which results in the typical for the Sicilian Defense double-edged position} (
10. Bxf6 {makes no sense here as White does not even get extra material for
giving up his dark squared bishop} Bxf6 11. Qxd6 $2 Qxf2 $17) 10... O-O 11. g4
Qc7 12. h4 b5 13. h5 Ne5 $11 14. Nd4 b4 15. Nce2 Nc4 16. Qe1 Qa5 17. Kb1 Qxg5
18. Nf5 exf5 19. f4 Qxg4 20. Rg1 Qf3 21. Rg3 Qxh5 22. Rh3 Qg6 23. Rg3 Ng4 24.
Nd4 Bh4 25. Bxc4 Bxg3 26. Qxg3 Ne5 0-1

