63,45,44,112,102,139,152,197,203]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5.
Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. O-O-O O-O {A little later in my career, I
chose to test the main line against one of the most promising young stars at
the time: Ruslan Ponomariov.} 9. f4 h6 10. Bh4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Qa5 {By
comparison with the classical main line, in this position after 12.Bc4, there
is no move Bd7 but Black plays 12...e5 instead.} 12. Bc4 e5 13. fxe5 dxe5 14.
Qd3 Bg4 15. Rdf1 Be6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Kb1 $14 {My opponent played a fine
positional game, slowly outplaying me.} Qc5 18. Bb3 Kh8 19. h4 $16 {White has
the d5 square and a comfortable initiative meanwhile it is not clear where
Black's counterplay is. After putting some hours of work, I decided not to
play this system again and continued experimenting in the Rauzer...} Be7 20.
Qe2 Qc8 21. Bxe6 fxe6 22. Rxf8+ Qxf8 23. Qb5 Qc8 24. Ne2 Qc7 25. Nc1 Re8 26.
Qe2 Rf8 27. Nd3 Bd6 28. a3 Qf7 29. Rd1 Kh7 30. Ka2 Qc7 31. Ne1 Qc6 32. g3 Bc7
