1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7 {This game proved to be a turning point for me making me rethink my
opening choices. My opponent played very well and the loss greatly upset me.
Even worse was the fact that it was played at a team championship and I let my
teammates down.} 9. f3 Be7 10. h4 h6 11. Be3 h5 {Again, the well-known idea of
pushing the bishop back and preventing g4} 12. Bg5 Ne5 13. Qe1 Qc7 14. f4 Neg4
{During the game, I was happy with my position after the oppening stage
getting the type of play I wanted. Unfortunately, my opponent played the
middlegame very creatively while I lost the thread at some point} 15. Rh3 {
[%cal Yh3d3]} b5 16. a3 Rc8 17. Rd2 Qb8 18. Rhd3 {It is very unusual for White
to have his rooks doubled on the "d" file like this but here Dave managed to
make it work! The resulting position is very complicated and each side has
plenty of options} e5 $13 19. Nf5 Bxf5 20. exf5 O-O 21. Be2 Bd8 22. Bxg4 Nxg4
23. Bxd8 Rfxd8 24. Nd5 Re8 25. f6 e4 26. Rg3 e3 27. Rd3 Rc5 28. fxg7 Qc8 29.
Kb1 Qf5 30. Nxe3 Qxf4 31. Rf3 Qh6 32. Qg3 Ne5 33. Nf5 Qg6 34. Rxd6 Qxg3 35.
Rxg3 Ng6 36. Rg5 Rc4 37. Rxh5 b4 38. Rxg6 1-0

