1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 {My suggestion to the
readers is to look at games by strong players who frequently employ the
Rauzer- Vidit, Maghsoodloo, Demchenko, Gupta, Kozul- in order to better
comprehend the ideas of the opening} 6. Bc4 {I believe 6.Bc4 is not as
dangerous as 6.Bg5} e6 {White has 2 setups to choose from: one involves
castling kingside, and the other queenside. I believe 0-0-0, or the so-called
Velimirovic attack, is more challenging to face as Black} (6... Qb6 {is GM
Shankland's recommendation}) (6... Bd7 {has also been played quite a lot}) 7.
Be3 (7. Bb3 Be7) 7... Bd7 {I believe this to be the best move order} 8. O-O ({
The Velimirovic attack:} 8. Qe2 {Here I delay Be7} a6 9. Bb3 (9. O-O-O b5 10.
Nxc6 Bxc6 11. Bb3 Qc7 {is a nice game of Kozul's who is arguably one of the
most experienced players in the Rauzer} 12. Bd4 Be7 {time to develop the
pieces and castle since the king cannot stay too long in the center} 13. Bxf6
Bxf6 14. Nd5 $6 Bxd5 15. exd5 e5 {Despite the opposite-colored bishops, the
game is still far from a draw. The position bears more risks for White as his
bishop is somewhat isolated on b3} 16. h4 O-O 17. g4 {is an attempt at an
attack but in reality White does not have anything} g6 18. g5 Bg7 {the bishop
parries all possible threats against the king} 19. Kb1 Rfb8 $15 {Black
launches his own counterplay} 20. c3 a5 21. Bc2 b4 22. c4 b3 $1 {A beautiful
sacrifice aimed at opening lines against the king! When going for an attack,
material is not important, initiative is what matters!} 23. axb3 a4 $1 $19 24.
Rh3 e4 25. Kc1 axb3 26. Bxb3 Qc8 27. Re3 Rb4 28. Kc2 Rab8 29. f3 Qb7 {0-1 (29)
Kadric,D (2562) -Kozul,Z (2614) Bihac 2016}) 9... b5 10. O-O-O Qc7 (10... b4 $2
{is premature since Black is underdeveloped}) {White can try a couple
different options to start an attack:} 11. f3 (11. g4 {demonstrates the
advantage of the White queen being on e2 and not d2: there is no need to waste
time to play f3} b4 12. Na4 (12. Nd5 $2 {does not give White sufficient
compensation} exd5 13. exd5 Nxd4 14. Bxd4+ Kd8 15. g5 Ng8 $17 {The king is
safe on d8 and with a little patience Black is going to regroup and take over})
(12. g5 bxc3 13. gxf6 cxb2+ 14. Kxb2 gxf6 $15 {is in Black's favor. Black has
an extra pawn and his king is safe}) 12... Nxd4 $146 (12... Rb8 $5) 13. Bxd4
Bb5 {an important intermezzo pushing the White queen away} 14. Qe1 a5 15. f4
Rc8 {going for a queenside initiative} 16. Kb1 Nd7 $13 {Black achieved a sharp
position with good counterplay and chances for a win}) (11. f4 Na5 {
controlling the light squared bishop and preparing b4} 12. Bf2 (12. e5 dxe5 13.
fxe5 Qxe5 14. Nf3 Nxb3+ 15. axb3 Qc7 $17 {1/2-1/2 (34) Qiao,L (2376)-Song,B  
(2097) Suzhou 2001} 16. Bd4 Be7 17. Ne5 Bc6 $17 {1/2-1/2 (34) Qiao,L (2376)
-Song,B (2097) Suzhou 2001}) 12... b4 13. Na4 e5 {In the Sicilian Defense,
Black needs to know precise theory in order not to end up worse: the correct
idea played a move earlier or later can turn into a blunder. The central break
13...e5 narrowly works out} (13... Nxb3+ 14. axb3 Be7 $11) 14. fxe5 dxe5 15.
Bg3 Nxb3+ 16. axb3 Rc8 $15 {Black has accumulated a number of positional
pluses, namely the bishop pair, the isolation of Na4, and a comfortable space
advantage. At first, it seems that he has played against the opening rules:
delaying kingside development and castling, but in fact the great dynamics of
the position more than compensates! That is why we all love the Sicilian
defense!} 17. Kb1 h5 $5 (17... Be7 $5 18. Nf5 Bb5)) 11... Be7 12. g4 b4 {
The knight does not have a good square since Qe2 blocks its path} 13. Na4 (13.
Nb1 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bb5 (14... O-O $5 15. g5 Nh5 $19 {[%cal Ga6a5,Ga5a4]}) 15.
Qg2 O-O 16. g5 Nh5 17. Qg4 g6 18. f4 Bd7 19. Qf3 a5 $40 {0-1 (35) Viel,S (2220)
-Travadon,L (2348) Belfort 2017}) 13... Nxd4 14. Bxd4 (14. Rxd4 $2 Qa5 $19)
14... Bb5 {pushing the queen to a worse square} 15. Qe1 a5 (15... O-O) 16. Kb1
O-O $13 {The position is complicated but I believe Black has great chances
because of the awkwardly placed Na4}) (8. f4 {another possible setup is f4,
Qf3 and 0-0-0} Be7 9. Qf3 Rc8 {[%cal Rc8c4]} 10. O-O-O (10. Bb3 Nxd4 11. Bxd4
b5 {active play} 12. Bxa7 $6 {is too greedy and leads to a worse position for
White} b4 $6 (12... Bc6 $17 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gd8a5]}) 13. Ne2 Bc6 14. Ng3 {Black
has enough compensation for the pawn and can afford to play on both sides of
the board. Pushing the White knight with h5-h4 is to follow} h5 $44 {1/2-1/2  
(35) De Firmian,N (2552)-Reeh,O (2416) Germany 2002}) 10... Nxd4 11. Rxd4 Qa5 (
11... b5 $5 12. Bb3 Bc6) 12. Bb3 Rxc3 {The typical Sicilian sacrifice!} (12...
O-O {0-1 (81) Sundaram,S-Wang,A Dreaming King 2020 2020 [HP2018]}) 13. bxc3 O-O
$44 {Black does not need to rush with recapturing since he enjoys lasting
compensation due to weakness of the White king.}) 8... Be7 9. Bb3 (9. f4 {
[%csl Yd7][%cal Yd8d5,Yd6d5] is possible to play here since Black does not
have the d5 break (Bd7 blocks the file)} O-O 10. Qf3 (10. f5 {[%csl Re5]
attacking e6 and trying to provoke e5 thus taking control over the light
squares. However, pushing f5 also gives up the important e5 square}) 10... Qc7
$5 (10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6) 11. Bb3 (11. Bd3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 13. fxe5 (13.
Be3 b5 14. Nxb5 Bxb5 15. Bxb5 Qxc2 $13) 13... dxe5 14. Qg3 {[%cal Yg3c7] a
well-known attacking idea. Nonetheless, Black is just in time to play 14...Bc5
and alleviate the pressure on his king} Bc5 15. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 16. Kh1 {moving
away from the pin} Kh8 $11 {Ejsmont,K (2100)-Adamski,M (2275) Krynica 2003} (
16... Qe7)) (11. Ndb5 Qb8) 11... Nxd4 $146 12. Bxd4 Bc6 (12... b5 13. e5 dxe5
14. fxe5 $14) 13. f5 (13. Qg3 b5 14. e5 dxe5 15. fxe5 Ne4 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 $15)
13... e5 14. Be3 b5 15. Bg5 Nxe4 (15... Rac8 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Rf2) 16. Bxe7
Nf6 17. Bd5 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Qg3 f6 20. Bxf8 Rxf8 $44) 9... O-O 10. f4 {
it is the main move by far} (10. Ndb5 {is not dangerous as Black is able to
defend d6 without any trouble} Qb8 {the queen also supports a6, b5} 11. f4 {
[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5]} (11. Bf4 Ne5 {ofc not going for e5 which would be a
positional mistake})) (10. Qe2 {side line} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 (11... b5 {
might also be possible. However Black surrenders the bishop pair} 12. Nxb5 Nxe4
{is a novelty I thought about which might be worth checking out. Black has
compensation} 13. Nxa7 d5) 12. Rad1 Qa5 {just normal position} 13. f4 e5 {
a little unusual idea which works tactically. We normally push b5 but here e5
is intersting as well} 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Rf5 $2 Bc5 {the key move of the line})
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 (11. Qxd4 {surrenders the initiative} Ng4 $15 12. Rad1 (12.
Bd2 {White cannot save dark squared bishop:} Bf6 $19 13. Qxd6 Be7 14. Qd4 Rc8 {
[%cal Ye7c5,Yg4f2,Yc5g1] winning material}) 12... b5 $146 13. f5 (13. Bc1 Rc8 {
[%cal Gd6d5]}) 13... b4 14. fxe6 fxe6 15. Nd5 exd5 16. Bxd5+ Kh8 17. Bxa8 $19)
11... Bc6 12. Qe2 {the right move order for White} (12. e5 $6 {is dubious for
White. The same idea works much better in the 7...a6 (instead of 7...Bd7) line
where after pushing e5 White can go Ne4--> Nd6 sacrificing a pawn for the
initiative} dxe5 13. fxe5 Nd7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7c5] where we target the e5
pawn, White does not have any threats}) (12. Qd3 {gives Black an additional
posiibility as opposed to the main line 12.Qe2} b5 13. Nxb5 Bxe4 $1 {the
reason why 12.Qe2 is a more desirable move}) 12... b5 13. Nxb5 Bxb5 14. Qxb5
Nxe4 {the main line. Even though Black has given up the bishop pair, his
position is not worse because White has weakened kingside with f4} 15. f5 {
Black applies a dark squared strategy:} (15. Rad1 d5 16. Qd3 Nd6 17. c4 dxc4
18. Bxc4 {1/2-1/2 (62) Michiels,B (2501) -Hirneise,T (2446) Germany 2012} Qc7
19. Bb3 Nf5 $13) 15... e5 16. Be3 (16. Qe2 Ng3 $5 17. hxg3 exd4 $15) 16... Bg5
{Exchanging the active Be3} (16... Nf6 17. Bg5) 17. Qe2 $6 Bxe3+ $17 18. Qxe3
Nf6 19. Rad1 Qc7 20. Rd2 a5 21. a4 Rab8 22. h3 h6 {nice prophylaxis} 23. Rfd1
Rfd8 24. Kh1 Rb4 25. Rd3 Rf4 {[%csl Ya4,Yc2,Yf5,Rg3,Rh2] Black enjoys a better
position due to the numerous weaknesses in White's camp} 26. Rc3 Qb7 {0-1 (40)
Kravtsiv,M (2549)-Balogh,C (2616) Beijing 2008} *

