{When we talk about typical structures in the Rauzer attack, we need to spot
what makes them different with respect to other Sicilian systems, such as the
Scheveningen or other branches of the Classical Sicilian. The early bishop
development to g5 increases the probability of exchanging it on g5. This can
lead to two main possibilities: 1) Black re-captures with a piece (usually the
queen or, more desirably, the bishop). In this case, White will try to
compensate for giving up the bishop's pair by either grabbing the initiative
at once or winning the pawn on d6. 2) In avoidance of White's ideas described
above, Black takes on f6 with the g-pawn. This is the most typical situation
distinguishing the Rauzer structures among the Sicilian ones in general.
Before examining the situation described under 2), we will see a game
illustrating Black's ideas in the first situation.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O h6 9. Be3 Nxd4 10. Bxd4
b5 11. f4 Be7 12. Bd3 b4 13. Ne2 Qa5 {This looks more like a Scheveningen,
with an extra tempo for Black, ...h7-h6, which can also be considered as a
slightly weakening move. The game really becomes typical for the Rauzer after
the following exchange.} 14. Bxf6 $146 Bxf6 15. Bc4 {WHite defends on a2 and
attacks d6. The latter will turn out to be illusory, though.} ({Salov analyses
} 15. e5 {, which is White's alternative idea after giving up the bishops'
pair. However, White does not obtain enough initiative:} dxe5 16. Be4 Ra7 17.
Qd6 (17. Bc6+ Kf8 18. Qd6+ Be7 $17) 17... Be7 (17... Qc7 $2 18. Bc6+ Bd7 19.
Bxd7+ Qxd7 20. Qb8+ $18) 18. Qc6+ Bd7 19. Rxd7 Rxd7 20. Rd1 Qc7 21. fxe5 Kd8 (
21... Bg5+ 22. Kb1 Ke7 23. Rxd7+ Qxd7 24. Qc5+ Kd8 25. Nd4 $40) 22. Nd4 Bg5+
23. Kb1 {Until this point, Salov's analysis has been irreproachable. A good
illustration of the players' mental strength before computers. However, he now
underestimates Black's chances.} Qxc6 $6 ({Black could neutralise WHite's
initiative completely by playing} 23... Be3 $1 $19 {Marin}) 24. Bxc6 Kc7 25.
Bxd7 Kxd7 26. h4 Bd8 $15) 15... O-O $1 {Sacrificing the pawn on d6 and making
the game relevant for the corresponding situation mentioned above.} (15... Be7
{is a bit slow, allowing White to get reasonable play:} 16. Kb1 O-O 17. h4 {
[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] Marin}) 16. Qxd6 {Once he had said "A"...} (16. h4 $2 d5 $1
{yields Black decisive initiative for the pawn:} 17. exd5 exd5 18. Qxd5 (18.
Bxd5 Rd8 $19) 18... Qc7 {[%cal Gc8g4] Marin White's pieces are vulnerable and
both wings are weak.} 19. Qxa8 Qxc4 {[%csl Rb2,Re2][%cal Gc4a2] only
accelerates the process.}) 16... Bb7 {The bishops' combined pressure along the
long diagonals is very hard to meet. White's minor pieces do not have good
squares and the queen is vulnerable, too.} 17. Qd3 (17. e5 Rfd8 $19 {traps the
queen. Marin}) 17... Rfd8 ({Salov indicates} 17... Qc5 $5 {as an interesting
alternative.} 18. e5 (18. Ng3 {Marin} Rfc8 19. Bb3 a5 20. Ba4 Ba6 $19) 18...
Rfd8 19. Nd4 Bh4 $44 {Salov. Once again, Salov is too modest. Black is winning,
due to the bishops' hyper-activity. This is the first moment when we see the
slightly curious bishop's move to h4.} 20. Rd2 (20. Rhf1 Bxg2 21. Rg1 Bf2 $19 {
[%cal Gd8d4,Gd4c4]}) 20... Bf2 $1 21. c3 (21. Rxf2 Rxd4 $19 {[%cal Gd4c4]})
21... bxc3 22. bxc3 Qa3+ {[%cal Gb7g2,Ga8b8] Marin}) 18. Qe3 Rdc8 $1 {Forcing
the bishop to make up his mind.} 19. Bb3 {Since White will not be in time to
start an attack with f4-f5, the bishop will be passive and exposed on this
square. Due to the hanging pawn on a2, there was nothing better, though. As an
important consequence of the last move, the bishop on b7 has no opponent along
the long light diagonal now.} Qc5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ga6a4] A very strong,
though slightly paradoxical move. Salov does not mind exchanging his strongest
piece and thus reducing his chances for a mating attack. The point is that the
white queen was the only piece that could keep White's position together. In
the ensuing queenless middlegame, the bishops' pressure will be overwhelming.}
20. Qxc5 Rxc5 21. Ng3 a5 22. Ba4 Bh4 $1 {Again this irritating move. the
bishops' cooperation is obvious.} 23. Rhe1 (23. Rd2 Bxg3 24. hxg3 Bxe4 $17 {
Marin White's bishop is still out of play and the kingside pawns are
vulnerable.}) (23. Rd4 Rac8 $5 $17) 23... g5 $1 {A very important move,
finally gaining the control over the most important dark squares. The game is
strategically decided.} 24. fxg5 (24. Rd7 $142 gxf4 25. Rxb7 fxg3 26. hxg3 Bxg3
$17) (24. f5 exf5 {[%cal Gh4e1]} 25. exf5 Bxg2 $19 {Marin}) 24... Bxg5+ 25. Kb1
Rd8 26. Rd3 Ba6 27. Rxd8+ Bxd8 28. Re3 h5 $1 29. a3 h4 30. axb4 (30. Nh1 Bb6
$19) 30... Rg5 $1 $19 (30... axb4 $19 {Marin}) 31. b5 Bb7 32. Rd3 Bb6 {
Fantastic bishops' regrouping (Marin)} 33. Rd6 (33. Rd7 hxg3 34. h4 Bxe4 35.
hxg5 Bxg2) 33... hxg3 34. h4 Rg4 35. Rxb6 Bxe4 36. Rc6 Bxg2 37. b6 Rxa4 38. b7
Rb4 39. Rc8+ Kg7 40. b8=Q Rxb8 41. Rxb8 Bd5 0-1

