{[%evp 0,67,38,38,46,63,71,19,40,9,9,17,73,45,79,57,67,56,67,37,42,49,63,57,50,
58,59,48,49,41,95,49,49,49,53,61,60,34,40,67,87,69,87,84,83,83,104,95,111,123,
126,149,189,165,195,211,211,214,211,205,195,169,250,260,260,243,287,296,263,
313] We will switch now to the second (and even more) typical situation, with
the doubled pawns on the f-file. The most outstanding early promotor of this
structure from Black's point of view was Botvinnik. One of his most famous
wins with it was examined by grandmaster Grigorov in his webinar on Rauzer
endings. Botvinnik's general plan had one important drawback, though. He
refrained from ...b7-b5, in order to maintain the possibility of castling long.
This offers White certain freedom of action, as illustrated by this game.} 1.
e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 h6 8. Bxf6
gxf6 9. O-O-O a6 10. f4 {In a theoretical line we will see later, Black has ...
Bd7 instead of ...h7-h6, allowing him to play ...b7-b5. Botvinnik did not want
that, though. Black's central structure is compact and likely to provide the
black king with a reliable shield. White's most natural (and almost the only
constructive) plan is to attack on light squares with f4-f5.} h5 11. Kb1 Bd7
12. Be2 Qb6 13. Nb3 $1 {An important novelty over a game played by Keres half
a year earlier. Without queens, Black has very comfortable play.} (13. Rhf1
Qxd4 14. Qxd4 Nxd4 15. Rxd4 h4 16. f5 Rc8 17. Rd3 $11 Rc5 $5 18. fxe6 fxe6 19.
Rxf6 Rg5 20. Rf2 Rhg8 {Black has excellent compensation for the pawn, Keres,
P-Petrosian,T Amsterdam/Leeuwarden 1956 (½-½, 41) Please refer to the
webinar held by grandmaster Grigor Grigorov/ Such endgames, even with a pawn
less, are almost always comfortable for Black.}) 13... O-O-O 14. Rhf1 {By
refraining from ...b7-b5, Black has got himself certain space problems. The
next move aims at solving them.} Na5 15. Rf3 (15. Nxa5 Qxa5 16. Rf3 Kb8 17. Qd4
Be7 (17... Rg8 $16 {Marin} 18. g3 Bc6 19. Qxf6 Qc7 20. Qd4 Bg7 21. Qd2 f5 $132)
18. b4 Qc7 19. Nd5 exd5 20. Rc3 Bc6 21. exd5 $18 {Keres Even though Black can
slightly improve earlier, this line is suggestive for his latent problems when
keeping the pawn on b7.}) 15... Nxb3 16. axb3 Kb8 17. Na4 Qa7 {Botvinnik
intends to maintain control over all the important squares, hoping that he
will neutralise the initiative and then enjoy his play on dark squares.} (17...
Bxa4 18. bxa4 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7][%cal Gf3b3]}) (17... Qc7 18. Qd4 Bc6 (18... Be7
19. Rc3 Bc6 20. Nb6 {Keres}) 19. Rc3 (19. Qxf6 Rg8) 19... d5 20. exd5 Rxd5 21.
Qxf6) 18. f5 $16 Be7 ({According to Keres, the best chance was} 18... exf5 19.
exf5 Bc6 {Keres However, Botvinnik was not the kind of player to make such
concessions.} 20. Qa5 Be7 21. Rc3 {[%cal Ge2f3]}) 19. fxe6 fxe6 {Black needs
just one tempo to kick back with either ...b7-b5 or ...Bc6 followed by ...
d6-d5.} 20. Rxf6 $1 {This winning combination, justified by White's superior
activity and coordination, is by far less simple than it may look.} Rh7 {
[%cal Gb7b5] Black defends the seventh rank, preparing to push the knight back
with ...b7-b5. Under different circumstances, this would yield him good play
on dark squares, but Keres will know how to maintain his pressure.} (20... Bxf6
$2 {is obviously bad in view of} 21. Qxd6+ Ka8 22. Nb6+ {Once again, we notice
the space problems caused by refraining from ...b7-b5.}) (20... Bxa4 $2 21.
Rxe6 {attacking two bishops.}) ({The critical continuation was} 20... b5 21.
Rf7 Be8 22. Rg7 $3 ({A calm move, maintaining the pin along the seventh rank.
Keres rightly considers it stronger than} 22. Rxe7 Qxe7 23. Nc5 {He evaluates
that White has a fine attacking position.} dxc5 $1 24. Qxd8+ Qxd8 25. Rxd8+ Kc7
26. Rd3 Rf8 27. Rh3 Kd6 $5 {Defending the c5-pawn in advance and preparing
either ...Rf4 or ...Rf2.} 28. Bxh5 Rf1+ $1 {Pushing the white king far from
the centre.} 29. Ka2 Bxh5 30. Rxh5 Rf4 31. e5+ Kd5 {With the white king
passive, the win is highly problematic.}) 22... bxa4 23. Qb4+ Ka8 (23... Kc8
24. Rxe7 Qxe7 25. Bxa6+ {mating next.}) (23... Bb5 24. bxa4 {retrieves the
bishop, maintaining two extra pawns and an attack with opposite-coloured
bishops.}) 24. e5 $1 {The only winning move.} Bc6 25. exd6 $18 {(main line
given by Keres).}) 21. Rg6 $1 ({More active than} 21. Rff1 {, which would
offer Black some chances to consolidate.}) 21... b5 22. Nc3 Qc5 {Black tries
to consolidate, but the next knight move ke4eps him troubled.} 23. Na2 $1 {
Heading for d3.} Ka7 24. Nb4 Rf8 25. Bf3 h4 26. h3 Bc8 (26... Be8 27. Rxe6 Bd7
28. Rg6 Be8 29. Nd3 {followed by Rh6. (Keres)}) 27. Nd3 Qc7 28. Nf4 Rf6 29. Bg4
Rxg6 ({Against} 29... Rhf7 {Keres gives the elegant line} 30. Nxe6 Bxe6 31.
Bxe6 Rxg6 32. Bxf7 {winning.}) 30. Nxg6 Bb7 $2 {A blunder in a lost position.}
31. Bxe6 Bd8 ({Keres believes that Botvinnik overlooked that} 31... Bxe4 {
runs into} 32. Qd4+) 32. Bd5 Bxd5 33. Qxd5 Rf7 34. e5 1-0

