{[%evp 0,124,29,31,50,50,82,61,52,39,39,30,39,36,35,23,57,39,44,20,22,37,35,17,
22,-23,1,19,13,5,-4,-13,-1,-23,14,18,17,38,40,71,71,74,68,56,78,61,58,57,35,43,
45,33,12,12,22,40,40,24,19,18,49,10,7,8,2,-14,18,0,0,0,0,0,14,38,86,37,57,71,
92,86,97,81,82,87,93,87,138,87,87,88,88,79,80,78,84,93,98,102,109,94,127,132,
142,151,151,151,151,148,155,155,155,155,155,144,189,94,127,341,394,403,409,419,
431,423,436,436,476] We switch now to the modern versions of this structure,
involving ...b7-b5. We will start with a warning about the further advance of
the b-pawn. In certain occasions, it is better to keep ...b5-b4 in reserve!} 1.
e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O
Be7 9. f4 Bd7 10. Nf3 b5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 (11... Bxf6 $2 {loses the central pawn
without any compensation, since White is more active, too.} 12. Qxd6 Bxc3 13.
bxc3 Ra7 14. Be2 $16 {Grabbing the d6-pawn is one of the situations mentioned
above, regarding Black?s attempt to capture on f6 with a piece..}) 12. f5 h5
13. Kb1 Qb6 14. Bd3 Ne5 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Rhf1 {The position is relatively
stable, but White is better developed. Black tries to compensate for it by his
good conctrol in the centre. White?s main positional threat is Ne2-f4,
starting to build up his pressure on light squares.} b4 $2 {This not only
wastes a tempo (the knight was heading for f4 anyway), but more importantly,
gives up the control over the c4-square.} (16... Rg8 $6 {fails to prevent} 17.
Ne2 $1 Rxg2 18. Qh6 O-O-O 19. Nf4 Rf2 20. Nxe5 dxe5 21. Ng6 Bd6 22. Qxh5 {
with certain pressure for White, plus the potential danger of advancing the
h-pawn.}) (16... Qc5 $5 {such a neutral move is better than the game move.} 17.
Ne2 (17. g3 {deprives White of later knight access to g3, allowing Black to
switch plans.} b4 18. Ne2 Nxd3 19. cxd3 e5 20. Nh4 a5 {[%cal Re2g3] In the
absence of the possibility of Ng3, Black is doing fine.}) 17... Ng4 18. Rde1 (
18. Ned4 {allows} Nxh2 19. Nxh2 Qxd4) 18... Ne3 19. Rg1 Bf8 20. Ned4 Nc4 {
This is the point. In a similar line below, the knight will not have this
square.} 21. Bxc4 bxc4 $13) (16... O-O-O $1 {is probably best.} 17. Ne2 (17. h3
Rdg8) (17. g3 Ng4 18. Rde1 Kb8) 17... Ng4 18. Rde1 Ne3 19. Rg1 d5 $1 {with
certain initiative.}) 17. Ne2 Ng4 (17... Nxd3 18. cxd3 e5 19. Nh4 a5 20. Ng3
$16 {[%csl Gf5] With this square available for the knight, Black's position is
bad.}) 18. Rde1 Bf8 (18... Ne3 19. Rg1 Bf8 20. Nf4 Bh6 21. g3 {[%cal Re3c4] No
retreat to c4 now.} Ng4 22. h3 Ne5 23. Qe2 {similar to the game}) 19. Nf4 Bh6
20. g3 $14 Ne5 (20... e5 21. Nd5 Bxd2 22. Nxb6 Bxe1 23. Nxa8 $16) 21. Qe2 Bxf4
22. gxf4 Nxd3 23. Qxd3 {After giving up control over the dark squares, Black's
position is not too appealing.} O-O-O 24. Qd2 Rhg8 25. c3 b3 26. axb3 Qxb3 27.
Nd4 Qb6 28. Qf2 Qb7 29. Rg1 Rxg1 30. Qxg1 e5 31. Nf5 Be6 32. Qg6 Qb3 33. Ne7+
Kb7 34. Nd5 Bxd5 35. exd5 Qxd5 36. Qxf6 Re8 37. Qg6 Rg8 38. Qh7+ Ka8 39. fxe5
dxe5 40. Qxh5 Rg2 41. Qe8+ Ka7 42. Qe7+ Ka8 43. Qxe5 Qxe5 44. Rxe5 Rxh2 45. Re7
Kb8 46. Ka2 Rg2 47. Ka3 Rc2 48. Kb3 Rh2 49. c4 Rg2 50. Ka3 Rc2 51. b3 Rc3 52.
Ka4 Ka8 53. Rh7 Kb8 54. Rd7 Ka8 55. Kb4 Rh3 56. c5 Kb8 57. Ka4 a5 58. Rd6 Rc3
59. Rb6+ Kc7 60. Rb5 Kc6 61. Rxa5 Rc1 62. Kb4 Kd5 1-0

