{[%evp 0,68,19,15,48,48,71,47,45,42,42,42,44,44,52,40,40,44,35,12,28,32,32,4,5,
26,20,15,17,20,3,17,23,23,28,-20,-36,-11,-15,-15,-15,-4,-15,-46,-47,-45,-45,
-45,-28,-28,-36,-36,0,0,-34,-24,-24,-24,-24,-24,-13,-22,-22,-89,-77,-58,-58,
-96,76,-416,-427] The next examples feature the main elements of the typical
strategic fight. In principle, White plays on light squares and Black plays on
dark squares. The mutual plans interfere with eachother, of course and the
culmination many times comes on squares of different colours than those which
are in the limelight during the main plan.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nc6 7. Qd2 e6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 {This system
started becoming popular in the '60s and ever since Romanian players of
different generations brought certain contributions to the development of the
theory. It does not mean that this was only a Romanian speciality, but it
explains why I am aware of several important games played by Romanians,
examined below.} 10. Bxf6 gxf6 (10... Qxf6 $2 {allows White to switch to the
second favourable situation mentioned in the introduction:} 11. e5 $1 dxe5 12.
Ndxb5 Qd8 13. Nd6+ Bxd6 14. Qxd6 exf4 15. Ne4 $5 $16) 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Qe3 {
[%cal Gc3d5] Even in the early days of this variation, White understood that
the compact black centre is not easy to undermine. Therefore, Boleslavsky
introduced the last move in 1965 in the game quoted below. The main idea is
Nd5.} Qe7 $1 {This was introduced by Ghitescu, as an improvement to the
reaction of his countryman in the game against Boleslavsky. Black parries the
threat and prepares the activation of his queen with gain of time. The main
point is to maintain the dark-squared bishop's flexibility.} (12... b4 $2 13.
Nd5 {[%csl Gb4]} Bxd5 14. exd5 $16) (12... Be7 {commits the bishop, placing it
on a somewhat passive position.} 13. f5 Qd7 (13... b4 14. Ne2 e5 15. Ng3 h5 16.
h4 a5 17. Bc4 a4 18. Qe2 {yields White the better position, since the black
bishop is away from the favourable c1-h6 diagonal.}) 14. fxe6 fxe6 15. Be2 h5
16. Bf3 O-O-O 17. Ne2 {White starts to attack the weak light squares and pawns
in the black camp.} Bf8 18. Kb1 Kb8 19. Nf4 Bb7 (19... Bh6 20. Qb6+) 20. Nxh5
Qf7 21. Qb6 Rc8 22. Nf4 $18 {Boleslavsky,I-Pavlov,M Hamburg 1965 (1-0, 47)})
13. Bd3 (13. Be2 Qa7 $1 14. Qxa7 Rxa7 $11 {Byrne,R-Ghitescu,T Havana 1966  
(½-½, 32) As mentioned earlier, Black has a comfortable position after the
queens' exchange.}) 13... Qa7 $1 14. Qh3 {More consistent than the queen
exchange, of course.} b4 {The most precise move order.} (14... Qc5 {offers
White additional possibilities.} 15. Rhe1 $5 (15. f5 b4 16. Ne2 e5 {transposes
to the game}) 15... b4 $6 16. Nd5 $1) 15. Ne2 Qc5 16. f5 e5 {A typical
position. Black can give up control over d5 as long as the enemy knight is far
from it. In doing so, he ensures his king's safety and the overall stability
in the centre.} 17. Ng3 a5 {Black advances his pawn to a4, after which he has
two main threats, ...a4-a3 creating the potential threat of intruding with the
queen to b2 and ...b4-b3, opening files for the attack. White has to create
some kingside play.} 18. Nh5 {This allows Black to activate his bishop with a
gain of time, but remains the most reasonable move. It is strange that in what
seems a purely positional battle, timing and speed are essential.} (18. Kb1 $6
{is too slow} a4 19. Nh5 Be7 20. Qh4 a3 21. Nxf6+ Kd8 $19 {[%cal Gc5d4,Ga3b2]
with a decisive queenside attack.}) 18... Bh6+ (18... Be7 {is possible here,
too, but the game move is more active.} 19. Qg4 a4 (19... O-O-O 20. Qe2 a4 21.
Bc4) 20. Qg7 Rf8 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. Qxf6 a3 23. b3 Qe3+ 24. Rd2 Qd4 25. Re2
Qa1+ 26. Kd2 Qc3+ {with a probable draw.}) 19. Kb1 Bg5 {Ass we will see in the
next game, the bishop is quite effective on the c1-h6 diagonal. In this game,
though, g5 is only a transitory position, on the way to an even more active
diagonal.} 20. Qf3 Ke7 21. h4 Be3 22. Rh3 Bd4 $1 {How many Dragon Sicilian
fans would dream of having such pressure on dark squares!} 23. Qe2 d5 $2 {
In many Sicilian systems, Black's main idea is to break in the centre with ...
d6-d5, after having prepared everything more or less thoroughly. In this
specific structure, though, this pawn break offers White the blocking square
on e4, offering him enough play to maintain the equality.} (23... a4 $1 {
would have maintained Black's advantage.} 24. Bc4 (24. g4 b3 25. cxb3 axb3 26.
axb3 (26. a3 Rxa3 27. bxa3 Qxa3 $19) 26... Rhc8 $19) 24... Rac8 25. Rg3 (25. g4
Bxe4 26. Qxe4 Qxc4 27. Nf4 Rc5 28. b3 d5) (25. Nxf6 Kxf6 26. Qh5 Ke7 27. Qxf7+
Kd8 28. Be6 Ra8) 25... Rhg8 (25... Bxe4 26. Qxe4 Qxc4 27. Nf4 Rc5 28. Qb7+ Kf8
$2 29. Ne6+) 26. Rxg8 Rxg8 27. g4 h6 28. Ng3 a3 29. b3 Bb5 $19) 24. g4 h6 25.
exd5 Bxd5 26. Be4 (26. Nf4 Bc6 27. Be4 Rac8) 26... Bc4 27. Qd2 $5 {Ljubojevic
does not wish to force a draw by repetition. Objectively, the position remains
complicated, with mutual chances.} (27. Bd3 $11 {Black cannot afford to
exchange the light-squared bishops. With the exception of some special
situations, exemplified later, this exchange favours White.} Rac8 $2 {Gheorghiu
} 28. Bxc4 Qxc4 29. Rhd3 a4 30. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3e4]}) 27... Rad8 28. g5 hxg5 (
28... Rd6 $5 29. gxf6+ Kd7) 29. hxg5 Rd6 $1 (29... fxg5 30. Qxg5+ Kd7 (30...
Kd6 31. Ng7) 31. c3 bxc3 32. Rxc3) (29... a4 30. gxf6+ Kd7 31. c3 Kc7 32. cxd4
Rxd4 33. Qe1 Rxd1+ 34. Qxd1 Rd8 35. Qe1 a3 36. Rh2 b3 37. axb3 Bxb3 38. Rh3
Rd1+ 39. Qxd1 Bxd1 40. Rc3 Qxc3 41. bxc3 Bxh5 42. Ka2) 30. b3 (30. g6 Rhd8 31.
Nxf6 (31. b3 Bc3)) 30... Bb5 31. g6 (31. gxf6+ Kd7 32. Qg5 Bc6 33. Bxc6+ (33.
Bd3 Qc3) 33... Rxc6 34. Rc1 e4 35. Qg7 e3 36. Qxf7+ Kc8 37. Rh4 e2 38. Rxd4
Qxd4 39. Qe7 Qh4 40. Ng7 Qxf6 41. Qe4 $44) 31... Rhd8 32. Bd3 $2 {The decisive
mistake in an interesting position.} (32. Nxf6 $1 Rxf6 (32... Kxf6 33. Rh7 Rf8
34. g7 Rg8 35. Rh8) 33. g7 Rg8 34. Qg2 Bc6 35. Rh8 Qc3 36. Rxd4 exd4 37. Rxg8
Qe1+ 38. Kb2 Qc3+ {with a perpetual.}) 32... e4 $1 33. Qe1 (33. Bxe4 Bc3) (33.
Bxb5 Bc3) 33... Be5 34. g7 (34. Qxe4 Qc3 35. Kc1 Qb2+ 36. Kd2 Rxd3+ 37. Rxd3
Rxd3+ 38. Ke1 Rxd1+ 39. Kxd1) 34... exd3 0-1

