{[%evp 0,59,16,28,46,47,80,66,66,57,58,58,82,43,59,63,53,39,37,66,66,30,30,6,9,
9,16,20,20,3,17,17,16,28,31,0,-26,-34,-35,-35,-35,-35,-10,-10,-18,-98,-83,-40,
-5,-36,-36,-28,-28,-28,-3,-28,-28,-28,-51,-46,-27,-33]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3.
d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 a6 6. Bg5 Nc6 7. Qd2 e6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10.
Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Qe3 Qe7 13. Bd3 Qa7 14. Qh3 b4 15. Ne2 Qc5 16. f5
e5 17. Ng3 a5 18. Nh5 Bh6+ 19. Kb1 Bg5 {a Few days later in the same
tournament, White improved with} 20. Qg4 $5 $146 {preventing the bishop's
transfer to e3-d4.} Ke7 21. h4 Bh6 (21... Be3 $2 22. Qg7) 22. Rh3 a4 23. Qe2 {
Both sides are well mobilised. The bishop on h6 is cutting like a blade,
preventing White from over defending c2 with either Rd2 or Rc1. In some cases,
if the c-file opens, there could be a mating threat on c1. However, White has
a clear plan, too. He intends to continue with g2-g4, followed by either Nxf6
or g4-g5. Black has to define his plans already. In doing so, he needs to take
into account certain tactical threats apart from the plan mentioned above.} Qd4
$5 {One of the two good moves.} (23... b3 $5 24. a3 (24. g4 bxa2+ $19 {with a
decisive attack.}) (24. cxb3 axb3 25. a3 Rhc8 {Threatening ...Bxe4 followed by
...Qc1 and mate.} 26. Rhh1 Ra4 $19) 24... bxc2+ 25. Qxc2 {with chances to
maintain the equality.}) (23... a3 $2 {runs into the strong} 24. Bc4 $1 {
[%cal Gb2b3,Gg2g4] Threatening b2-b3, after which play would be one-sided.}
axb2 {[%cal Gh6c1] Hoping for ...Bc1.} 25. Nxf6 $1 (25. Kxb2 Rhg8 $5 26. Nxf6
Kxf6 27. Qh5 Qxc4 28. Qxh6+ Rg6) 25... Kxf6 26. Qh5 Qxc4 27. Qxh6+ Ke7 28.
Qxd6+ Ke8 29. Qxe5+ Kf8 30. Qxh8+ Ke7 31. Qxb2 $18) 24. Nxf6 $1 {The only
chance to maintain the equality.} (24. Bc4 $6 Qxe4 25. Nxf6 (25. Qxe4 Bxe4 26.
Nxf6 Kxf6 27. Rxd6+ Kxf5 28. Rxh6 Bxg2 29. Rg3 Rhg8 30. Rxg8 Rxg8 31. Bxf7 Rg7
32. Be6+ Kf4) 25... Qxe2 26. Bxe2 Bxg2 27. Rg3 Bb7 28. Bf3 Kxf6 29. Bxb7 Rag8
$5 {with better chances in the endgame in both cases.}) (24. g4 $2 a3 25. c3
bxc3 26. b3 Bd2 $19) 24... a3 $1 (24... Kxf6 $2 25. Bc4 Qc5 26. Qh5 $18) 25. c3
$1 (25. c4 $2 Kxf6 $19) (25. bxa3 $2 bxa3 $19) 25... bxc3 26. Bc4 Bd2 $1 27.
Rxc3 $2 (27. bxc3 $1 {was more rforcing and stronger.} Rhb8+ 28. Bb3 Rxb3+ 29.
axb3 a2+ 30. Kb2 a1=Q+ 31. Rxa1 Bxc3+ 32. Rxc3 Rxa1 33. Qe3 Qxe3 34. Rxe3 Rg1 {
with approximately equal chances.}) 27... Kxf6 28. Qxd2 (28. Rxd2 Bxe4+ 29. Bd3
axb2) 28... Qxd2 29. Rxd2 Bxe4+ 30. Bd3 {Black prematurely agreed to a draw.
His chances in the endgame are better.} (30. Bd3 Bxd3+ 31. Rcxd3 Kxf5 32. Rxd6
e4 $17) 1/2-1/2

