{[%evp 0,60,23,23,52,40,40,14,4,12,27,27,51,20,81,50,45,32,29,9,30,35,29,35,39,
6,8,2,8,-43,-33,1,-6,-20,11,-15,9,4,0,4,-1,-19,16,-4,73,47,0,-15,9,-44,-30,-47,
-47,-41,-13,-33,-96,-250,-240,-242,-247,-448,-443]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6
gxf6 11. Kb1 Qb6 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. f5 {In the previous game, White did his
best to neutralise the dark-squared bishop's action by creating tactical
counterplay. This newer example shows how damaging such a bishop can be if
White does not take measures against it.} h5 (13... b4 14. Ne2 e5 {is the main
line, see the next games.}) 14. Bd3 $6 {This natural developing move actually
wastes a tempo with respect to the main line.} (14. fxe6 $1 fxe6 15. Bd3 {
is better, when Black cannot stabilise with ...e6-e5 anymore. True the
position remains interesting.}) 14... b4 15. Ne2 e5 {White is not in time to
reach an optimal configuration, due to the tempo wastes on Bd3. Besides, the
bishop absolves Black of problems on d6.} 16. Ng3 (16. h4 Bh6 17. Qe1 Ke7 $17)
16... h4 17. Nf1 Bh6 18. Qe2 Ke7 19. Nd2 a5 20. Bc4 a4 21. Nf3 $6 {Played
without a clear plan. Unless we can call Nxh4 "a plan".} b3 $1 {This is one of
the typical illustrations of Bronstein's discourse about the control over
light or dark squares. In this concrete case, it would sound like this: Black
controls the dark squares, but is it so important? White can place his pieces
and pawns on light squares. However, Bronstein later understood that the firm
control on dark squares may result into the weakness of the enemy light
squares, too. Black's pieces on dark squares may attack White's pieces and
pawns placed on light squares.} 22. cxb3 axb3 23. Bxb3 {Relatively best.} (23.
axb3 $2 Rhc8 24. Rhe1 Qa7 25. Qd3 (25. Kc2 Bb5) 25... Kf8 $5 26. Qxd6+ Kg7 27.
Qd3 Bb5 28. Kc2 Qa2 29. Nd2 Bxd2 $19) (23. a3 $2 Ra4 24. Qd3 (24. Bd5 Rc8)
24... Qc5 25. Bd5 Bxd5 26. exd5 (26. Qxd5 Qc2+ 27. Ka1 Rxa3+) 26... Rb8 27.
Rhe1 Kf8 $5 28. h3 e4 $1 29. Rxe4 Qc2+ 30. Qxc2 bxc2+ 31. Kxc2 Rxe4 $19) 23...
Ba4 $5 {An interesting moment. The exchange of the light-squared bishops is
supposed to favour White (compare with the comments to the game
Ljubojevic-Gheorghiu). In this concrete case, though, the last move is aimed
to exchange the only white piece providing the white king with defence.} (23...
Bb5 $1 24. Bc4 (24. Qe1 Rhb8 {is awfully passive for White. Just look how the
bishops dominate the white major pieces, which have only the first rank at
their disposal, and even that not entirely!}) 24... Qa6 25. Bxb5 Qxa2+ 26. Kc2
Rhc8+) 24. Rd3 (24. Bxa4 Rxa4 25. b3 (25. a3 Rxa3) (25. Rd3 Rha8 26. Rb3 Qxb3
27. axb3 Ra1+ 28. Kc2 Rc8+ 29. Kd3 Rxh1 30. Nxh4 Bg5 31. Nf3 Rcc1 32. Nxg5
Rhd1+ 33. Ke3 Re1) 25... Rha8 26. Rhe1 (26. Rhf1 Rxa2 27. Qxa2 Rxa2 28. Kxa2
Qa6+ 29. Kb1 Qb5 30. Kb2 Qe2+ 31. Kc3 Qxe4) 26... Rxa2 27. Qxa2 Rxa2 28. Kxa2
Qf2+ 29. Kb1 Qxg2 30. Rf1 h3 $19) 24... Bb5 25. Qc2 (25. Rhd1 $5 $17) 25...
Bxd3 26. Qxd3 Ra5 27. Nxh4 Rc5 28. Nf3 Rhc8 29. Nd2 Qb4 30. Rd1 Qxd2 0-1

