1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 Bd7 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O e6 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Kb1 Qb6 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. f5 b4 14. Ne2 e5
15. Ng3 {In this game, Black deviates a bit from the line examined earlier. We
will see a bit more of the paradox regarding the exchange of the light-squared
bishops.} Qc5 $5 16. b3 {A straightforward move, preparing Bc4.} (16. Nh5 $5) (
16. Bd3 $5) 16... h5 17. h4 Bb5 $2 {Black intends to prevent Bc4. Even though
the immediate capture on b5 would yield Black an attack along the a-file,
exposing the bishop to exchange at such an early stage looks risky (and is in
fact wrong).} ({The correct continuation is} 17... Ke7 18. Bc4 Bh6 19. Qe2 Bb5
$1 {Now this is well-timed since it creates a concrete threat, namely ... Bxc4.
} 20. Rd3 (20. Nxh5 Bxc4 21. bxc4 Qe3) (20. Bxb5 axb5 $19) 20... Bxc4 21. bxc4
Qxc4 22. Nxh5 Rhc8 23. g4 Rc5 24. Qg2 Rg8 25. g5 (25. Rhd1 $146 Ra5 26. Rb3 Be3
27. g5 fxg5 28. f6+ Kd8 29. Rxd6+ Kc7 $17) 25... Ra5 26. Rb3 fxg5 27. Rd1 g4
$13) 18. Qe1 $1 $146 {[%cal Gd1d5,Ge1b4] A deep thinker like Grischuk,
permanently in the search of the truth, both in analyse and over the board, is
the most indicated player for refuting Black's concept. The threat is Rd5,
winning the pawn on b4.} (18. Bxb5+ axb5 19. Qd5 Ra7 $11) (18. Be2 Ke7 $17 {
[%cal Gf8h6] Planning ...Bh6.} 19. c3 $2 {Suicidal.} bxc3 20. Qc2 Rg8 $19 {
Stefansson,H (2586)-Filipenko,A (2410) Pardubice 2001 (0-1, 27)}) 18... Rc8 {
What else?} (18... Ke7 19. Rd5 Qc6 20. Qxb4 $18) 19. Bxb5+ $1 {The point.
After the rook has left the a-file, White can afford to exchange on b5.} (19.
Rd2 $2 Bh6 $19) 19... axb5 20. Qe2 Ra8 (20... Rb8 21. Nxh5 Ke7 22. g4 Ra8 23.
Rh3 Qa7 24. c3 $18) (20... Ke7 21. Rd5 (21. Nxh5 Rxh5) 21... Qa7 22. Rxb5 Ra8
23. a4 bxa3 24. Ka2 $18) 21. Rd5 Qa7 22. Qxb5+ Kd8 23. a4 $1 {AFter the pawn
on b5 has been eliminated, White can parry the threats at leisure, retaining a
decisive positional advantage.} bxa3 24. Rhd1 (24. Ka2 Rg8 25. Qd3) 24... Be7
25. Qe2 Rc8 26. c4 Rg8 27. Nxh5 a2+ 28. Ka1 Rb8 29. R5d3 Qa3 30. Qc2 Rg4 31. c5
$1 {After having placed all his pieces on light squares, White breaks on dark
squares. More of Bronstein's discourse.} Rc8 32. Rc3 d5 33. Rxd5+ Ke8 34. g3
Qb4 35. Rc4 Qe1+ 36. Rd1 Qe3 37. Qd3 1-0

