{[%evp 0,24,19,38,40,41,66,66,66,48,52,26,65,25,7,39,39,29,46,58,54,-6,9,-53,
-54,-64,-64] For this course on Classical Sicilian, I tried to not only to
provide you with good middlegame understanding but also add a quick repertoire.
It should still be noted that the main goal of the lecture is to give you a
more thorough view of the d6-e5 structure} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {The Classical
Sicilian can be reached via different move orders (2...Nc6 or 2.. .d6) but I
prefer to stick to this one} 3. d4 Nf6 {By choosing 3...Nf6, I avoid the
Maroczy setups (the pawn structure with e4 and c4) and still transpose to the
main lines the vast majority of time} 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {The starting
position of the Classical Sicilian. In general, I believe most of the players
below 2300 tend to go for 6.Be3, 6.Be2 or 6.f3 where Black is able to get 6...
e5 and achieve a comfortable position} 6. f3 (6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3 (8.
Be2 {transposes}) 8... O-O 9. Qd2 a5) (6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 (7. Nf3 {dramatically
changes the dynamics of the position. The main difference between 7.Nf3 and 7.
Nb3 is that now Bg5 becomes a real threat: the Nxe4 trick would not work as
Bg5 is protected} h6 $1 {It is essential to prevent the bishop from going to
g5 as by taking on f6 White would establish firm control over d5} (7... Be7 {
is also playable according to computers, but I believe the human way of
handling the position is 7...h6} 8. Bg5 O-O 9. O-O Be6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nd5
$14 {[%csl Rd6,Rf6][%cal Rc2c3]}) 8. O-O Be7 9. h3 O-O 10. Re1 {[%cal Ye1e4,
Yc3d5,Ye2f1] overprotecting e4 and intending to go Bf1} (10. Be3 $6 {allows
Black to effortlessly carry out his central idea: the liberating d5 break} Be6
11. Qd2 Qc8 {The strongest move in the position: the queen makes room for Rd8
and with d5 to follow. With the queens on the board, after the exchange of e4
and d5 Black's advantage would be evident} (11... d5 {results in equality} 12.
exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Qxd5 Bxd5 15. Rfd1 Be6 16. c3 f5 {White gets
enough counterplay by putting pressure on e5 with Bb5} (16... g5) 17. Bb5 {
[%cal Rb5c6,Rf3e5]} Bf6 18. Rd6 $11) 12. Rfd1 Rd8 {[%cal Rd6d5]} 13. Qe1 d5 14.
exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. c3 Qe6) (10. Bc4 {does not help White cover the d5
square. Black develops with 10...Be6 and in case of exchange gets a good center
} Be6 11. Bxe6 fxe6 $15 12. Qe2 a6 13. Be3 d5 $17) 10... Be6 11. Bf1 {[%csl
Rd5][%cal Rf3e5,Re1e5,Rc3d5] having protected the e4 pawn White wants to play
Nd5 next move} Nb8 $1 {A curious maneuver: Black moves the knight away so that
he can capture Nxd5 in case White decides to jump. The Nb8 would go to d7
where he would be stopping c5 or navigate to f6 and support a kingside attack}
12. Nd5 (12. b3 a6 13. a4 Nbd7 14. Bb2 (14. Nd5 {including a4, a6 and then
going Nd5 benefits Black: after the inevitable exchange he can stop White's
pawn chain with a5} Nxd5 15. exd5 Bf5 16. c4 a5 $17 {[%csl Ra4,Rb3,Rc4,Rd5]
[%cal Rd7c5,Rf5h7,Rf7f5]}) (14. Ba3 Rc8 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Rc8c3]} 15. Nd5 Nxd5
16. exd5 Bf5 17. c4 a5 $15) 14... Rc8 15. Qd2 Qc7 16. Rad1 {[%csl Rc2,Rd6]} Qc6
{Black has achieved a balanced position with practical chances to win. He has
d5 under control and pressure along with the c file}) 12... Nxd5 13. exd5 Bf5
14. c4 Nd7 15. a3 Bg6 $15 {opening the way for the f pawn} (15... Qc7 {would
be a positional mistake. It leaves the Be7 unprotected and consecutively,
White can exploit the pinned e pawn via 17.Nd4 and taking charge of the light
squares} 16. b4 b6 17. Nd4 {[%csl Re7][%cal Rd4f5,Rd4c6,Re1e7]}) 16. b4 b6 17.
Bb2 f5 18. Rc1 Rc8 {[%cal Re7f6]} 19. Qb3 Bf6 $17 {[%cal Ye5e4,Yf5f4] Black
has a stable grip on the center with his mighty central pawns} 20. Kh1 e4 21.
Nd4 Bxd4 22. Bxd4 f4 $17 {[%cal Yd8h4,Yg6f5,Yf4f3]}) 7... Be7 8. O-O (8. Bg5 {
grants Black easy equality} O-O (8... Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Bxg5 10. Nxd6+ Ke7 11. Nxc8+
Rxc8 $11) 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. O-O Be6 11. Nd5 Bg5 12. c3 Ne7 $11) 8... O-O 9. Be3
a5 (9... Be6 $6 {[%cal Rd6d5]} 10. Bf3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rc3d5]}) 10. a4 {
White needs to go a4 to stop the advance of the pawn} (10. a3 a4 11. Nd2 d5 {
Black has solved his opening problems}) 10... Nb4 11. f4 Be6 12. Qd2 $6 (12. f5
{is premature} Bxb3 (12... Bd7 $15 {[%cal Yd7c6,Yd6d5] is another solid choice
for Black as he can break the center with d5 just in time}) 13. cxb3 d5 14.
exd5 Nfxd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bf2 e4 $11 {I find Black's position preferable
because of the strong e4 pawn White's wrecked queenside structure}) 12... Rc8 {
White's position is very tricky to navigate and he can easily lose in a matter
of a few moves if he is not careful} 13. Rad1 (13. Bd3 {loses material} Nxd3
14. cxd3 (14. Qxd3 Bc4 $19) 14... Bxb3 $19) (13. Bf3 exf4 14. Bxf4 Nxc2 15.
Qxc2 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 Bxb3 $17) (13. fxe5 dxe5 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Rb4c2]} 14. Rac1
Qc7 {[%csl Rc2,Rd2][%cal Rf8d8,Rd8d2,Rb4c2]} 15. Na1 {always sad to play such
a move} Rfd8 16. Qe1 Bc5 $19) (13. f5 Rxc3 $1 {the most direct way to prove
something has gone wrong for White} (13... Bxb3 14. cxb3 d5 15. exd5 Nfxd5 16.
Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Bf2 Bg5 18. Qe1 e4 {also gives Black serious positional advantage
}) 14. bxc3 (14. Qxc3 Nxe4 15. Qe1 Nxc2 16. Qxa5 Bxb3 $19) 14... Nxe4 15. Qc1
Nxc3 16. Bd3 Bd5 $19 {and it will soon be over for white}) (13. Kh1 $2 Nxe4 14.
Nxe4 Rxc2 15. Qe1 Bxb3 $19) 13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Rxc2 15. Qe1 Bxb3) 6... e5 {
[%csl Rd6,Re5][%cal Rc3d5]} 7. Nb3 {Achieving the desired d6-e5 pawn structure.
In this type of setup, the game revolves around fighting for the d5 square: if
Black manages to break through with d5 he would obtain a comfortable advantage;
if not he might experience slight problems. Logically, White's main idea is to
occupy d5 with his knight and play in the center/queenside} (7. Nde2 Be6 {
[%cal Rd6d5] Black inevitably goes for d5 on the next move opening his pieces.
White is not able to establish control on the square in time:} 8. Nd5 (8. Be3
d5) 8... Bxd5 9. exd5 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Nd4 {[%cal Rf6d5]} 11. Bd2 Be7 12. Bc4 Qc5
$17) (7. Nxc6 {does not pose Black problems} bxc6 {[%cal Rd6d5]}) 7... Be7 8.
Be3 (8. Bg5 {is not compatible with 7.Nb3: only Black can be fighting for an
edge after Nxe4:} Nxe4 9. Nxe4 (9. Bxe7 Nxc3 10. Bxd8 Nxd1 11. Rxd1 Kxd8 12.
Rxd6+ Kc7 13. Rd2 b6 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Rb6c5,Rb6a5] restricting Nb3. Black can
further progress gaining space on the kingside where he has a 4 vs 3 majority}
14. Bd3 Be6 15. Kf2 Rad8 16. Rhd1 g5 $11 {[%cal Rf7f5,Rh7h5]}) 9... Bxg5 10.
Nxd6+ $6 Ke7 $15 11. Nxc8+ Rxc8 {[%cal Rd8b6]} (11... Qxc8 {Both moves grant
Black a slight advantage and so choosing between them is a matter of style.
Personally, I believe leaving the queens on board gives Black more chances to
play for a win. However, a more positional player might pick the endgame after
Rc8 which also yields practical chances of a win}) 12. Qxd8+ Rhxd8) 8... O-O 9.
Qd2 {Having played f3, White's best option is to go for 0-0-0.} a5 {a critical
move for the line. Playing 9...a5, Black delays Be6 so that if White tries to
install Nd5, he can capture with Nxd5. Otherwise, with Be6, he would be forced
to play Bxd5 losing the bishop pair. Note: Stopping a5 with a4 is usually in
Black's favor since he gets the b4 square for Nc6} (9... Be6 $5 {is also
getting popular after Shankland suggested it in his book on the Classical
Sicilian} 10. Nd5 (10. O-O-O a5 11. Bb5 Nb4 12. a3 Qc7 13. Kb1 (13. axb4 Bxb3
14. cxb3 axb4 $15 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Rc7c1]}) 13... d5 14. axb4 d4 15. bxa5 Bxb3
16. cxb3 Qxa5 17. Ba4 dxc3 18. Qxc3 b5 19. Qxa5 Rxa5 20. Bd2 Rfa8 $11) 10... a5
11. c4 (11. Bb6 {is not dangerous} Qd7 12. Nc7 $6 a4 13. Nxa8 Rxa8 14. Nc1 a3
15. b3 d5 $19 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Re7b4,Rb4e1]}) (11. Nb6 $6 {is not great for
White either:} a4 12. Nxa8 Qxa8 13. Nc1 d5 $15 {[%cal Ya4a3,Ye7b4,Ye4d5,Yf6d5,
Yf8d8] White is underdeveloped while Black's pieces are too active}) {
Shankland's idea is to go} 11... a4 {with an unclear and highly interesting
position} 12. Nc1 b5 $5 {A second pawn sacrifice! Black is betting everything
on the initiative} 13. cxb5 $6 (13. Nxe7+ Nxe7 14. cxb5 d5 $44 {with
compensation}) 13... Bxd5 14. exd5 Nd4 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. Qxd4 a3 17. b3 Nh5 $19
{[%csl Re1][%cal Re7f6,Rf8e8,Re8e1,Rd8b6,Rb6a5]}) 10. Bb5 {the only sensible
way to prevent 10...a4. Here, I like to repeat the position once with Na7, Nc6
and put psychological pressure on the opponent. I believe White has no better
alternative than to repeat as well because all other moves have certain
drawbacks} (10. a4 Nb4 {[%csl Gb4,Yc2,Yd6][%cal Yb4d5,Yd6d5]} 11. Be2 Be6 12.
O-O d5 $19 {Black got everything he dreamed of}) (10. O-O-O {There couldn't be
a worse moment for White to castle queenside! After the natural 10...a4, Black
forces Nb3 to a1 and targets White's king} a4 11. Na1 a3 12. b3 Nb4 13. Kb1 Be6
$17 {[%cal Rd6d5] all the Black pieces come into play}) (10. a3 a4 11. Nc1 Be6
{[%cal Rd6d5]} 12. Nd5 $6 Bxd5 13. exd5 Nd4 {[%cal Rf6d5]} 14. Bxd4 exd4 15.
Qxd4 Qa5+ 16. Qd2 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Rb6g1,Rb6b2,Rf8e8,Re8e1]} 17. c4 Nd7 $19
{[%csl Re1][%cal Rf8e8,Re8e1] White comes under serious attack, his dark
squares are impossible to defend}) 10... Na7 11. Be2 (11. Ba4 {the White
bishop is out of play} Be6 12. O-O $2 Bc4 13. Rfd1 b5 $19) (11. Bxa7 $5 Rxa7
12. O-O-O Be6 (12... Qb6 13. a4 Be6 14. Kb1 Raa8 15. g4 Rfc8 16. h4 Ne8 17. Nd5
Bxd5 18. Qxd5 (18. exd5 Nc7 19. Be2 Qb4 $11 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Rb7b5]}) 18... Nc7
19. Qd3 Nxb5 $11) 13. Kb1 (13. Nd5 $4 Nxd5 14. exd5 Bg5 $19)) 11... Nc6 {
[%cal Ra5a4,Ra4a3]} 12. Bb5 (12. a4 Nb4) 12... Na7 13. Be2 Be6 14. O-O Nc8 {
[%cal Ra5a4,Ra4a3,Yc8b6,Yb6c4] re-routing the knight to a more active position}
15. a4 Nb6 {[%csl Rc4]} 16. Rfd1 $6 d5 17. exd5 Nfxd5 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Bf2 Qc7
$17 {[%cal Rf8d8,Rd8d2]} *

