{[%evp 0,68,19,31,72,53,68,67,67,46,46,27,72,31,26,25,25,-13,-15,-36,11,-2,-2,
-30,-60,-50,-60,-32,-45,-15,-15,-20,-57,-130,-121,-106,-106,-126,-57,-173,-77,
-76,-58,-138,-134,-153,-119,-159,-228,-229,-228,-212,-235,-224,-224,-224,-255,
-245,-270,-323,-342,-415,-415,-432,-193,-218,-288,-284,-297,-535,-468]} 1. e4
c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e5 {[%csl Rd6,Re5]} 7. Nf3
{[%csl Rb8]} Be7 {I would like to start with discussing the differences
between having Nc6 or Nb8: the main nuance is that with the knight still on b8,
Black always has the option to play Nbd7 and Nxf6 in case of Bg5} 8. g4 {
[%cal Rg4g5,Rc3d5]} (8. Bg5 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Rg5f6]} Nbd7 9. Bxf6 Nxf6 10. Bc4
b5 11. Bb3 (11. Bd5 $6 Rb8 {[%cal Yc8e6,Ye8g8,Yf6d5,Yb5b4,Yf7f5]} 12. O-O O-O {
[%cal Rb5b4,Rf6d5]} 13. a3 a5 14. Re1 b4 15. axb4 axb4 16. Na2 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 (
17. exd5 f5) 17... Be6 18. Qd2 Qb6 $15 {[%cal Rf8d8,Rd6d5]}) 11... Bb7 12. Qe2
b4 {making White go Nd5 before can better prepare it} 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5
Bxd5 15. exd5 Qa5 16. Qd2 Qb5 $17 {[%csl Rd5,Rd6,Re5][%cal Re7d8,Rd8b6,Ra6a4,
Re8g8] Black has a superior pawn structure (the White d5 pawn is weak ) and a
B vs N}) 8... h6 9. Rg1 (9. g5 {looks suspicious} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Nbd7 11. Rg1 b5
$15 {Black has harmonious development while White's pieces are poorly
coordinated}) 9... Qc7 (9... b5 $1) 10. Nh4 {[%cal Yh4g2,Yg2e3,Ye3d5]} (10. g5
hxg5 11. Nxg5 b5 12. a4 b4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 {[%cal Rd5f7,Rd5a8]} Bxg5 15.
Bxg5 (15. Qxa8 $4 Bb7 16. Qa7 Nc6 $19) 15... Bb7 16. Qd3 Nd7 17. Rd1 Nc5 18.
Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 Bxe4 20. Be3 Ne6 21. Rg4 {[%cal Rg4e4,Re4b4]} Bxc2 22. Rxa6)
10... g6 11. Ng2 Be6 12. Ne3 Nbd7 13. h4 {[%cal Yg4g5]} Qc6 14. Qf3 Nc5 {
targeting e4 from all sides} 15. Bg2 (15. Bd3 {after the game Firouzja said he
was concerned about this move. However, I believe his fears to be unfounded
due to:} b5 16. a3 Nxd3+ 17. cxd3 h5 18. g5 Nd7 19. Ned5 Nc5 $15 {[%cal Ye7d8]}
) 15... Na4 {[%csl Rc3,Rd5,Re4] removing the perfectly placed Nc3} 16. Ned5 (
16. Ncd5 Bxd5 17. exd5 Qc5 18. Qe2 b5 $11) 16... Nxc3 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Qxf6
Kd7 $17 {a highly original way to solve Black's problems} (18... Rh7 $19 {
is the engine's suggestion}) 19. g5 Nxe4 20. Qf3 d5 21. Qd1 Qb6 22. Be3 (22.
Bxe4 Qb4+ {a small tactic which ensures that Black retains the initiative})
22... Qxb2 23. Bxe4 Qb4+ 24. c3 Qxe4 25. Rb1 hxg5 26. Rb4 d4 27. cxd4 Ke8 28.
hxg5 Rh3 29. Kd2 Bf5 30. Qb3 Rc8 31. Rc1 Rxc1 32. Kxc1 Rh1+ 33. Kd2 b5 34. d5
Qf3 *

