{I believe this to be a great example of the ideas Black can use in the
Classical Sicilian} 1... Bd8 $1 {[%cal Yd8c7,Yd8a5] Maneuvring the Bishop to a
better diagonal. It is going to be far better placed on c7 from where it can
overprotect e5 (and thus support d5) and keep an eye on the a5 pawn} (1... Bg4
$5 {would be another way to accomplish the strategic goal of d5} 2. Re3 d5 $1 {
[%csl Re3,Rf3] requires some precise calculations} (2... Bxf3 {is not good
enough} 3. Rxf3 (3. gxf3 Nh5) 3... d5 (3... Rd8 4. c4) 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Be4 $18)
3. exd5 Nxd5 4. Nxe5 Nxe3 5. Nxc6 Bg5 6. fxe3 Qxc6 7. b3 Re8 8. Re1 Bh4) (1...
Nd7 {removes the knight from its perfect square} 2. Nc3 Nc5 3. Bf1 {[%cal
Rc3d5]}) 2. Nb6 (2. b3 Qxa5) (2. b4 {was probably better given what happened
in the actual game} Nh5 3. g3 Bg4 $11 (3... Nf6 {[%csl Rg3]}) 4. Qd1 (4. Be2
Rxc2) 4... Nf6 $15 {[%cal Rf6h7,Rh7g5]}) 2... Qb8 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Rd8b6]} 3.
Na4 Bc7 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rd6d5] the first step of the plan is complete} 4. Nc3
{trying to stop d5} Rd8 $17 (4... d5 $2 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Be4 $16) 5. Qe2 {
[%csl Re5][%cal Rf3e5] Black successfuly forced White into passive defense and
can now continues to improve his pieces. For example, the Bc7 has already done
its job preparing d5 and may switch to another more active position} Qc8 {
[%cal Yc7b8,Yb8a7,Ya7g1]} 6. Ra3 Bb8 7. h3 Ba7 {[%csl Ra7,Rc2][%cal Rc8c2]} 8.
Nh2 {[%cal Ya7c5,Yc5b4]} Bd4 9. Nd1 d5 $19 {finally breaking through} 10. exd5
Nxd5 {[%cal Yf7f5,Ye5e4] Once Black trades e4 for d5, he gets massive
initiative in the center and there is no stopping of his pawn majority} 11. Be4
Nf4 12. Qf3 Rc7 13. c3 Bc5 14. b4 Bd6 15. Bb1 f5 16. Ba2 Bxa2 17. Rxa2 e4 18.
Qe3 Nd3 19. Rf1 Bf4 20. Qe2 Nc1 21. Qc2 Nxa2 22. Qxa2+ Kh7 23. Qb1 Qd7 24. g3
Bd2 25. g4 Qd3 *

