{[%evp 0,31,19,31,72,53,68,72,66,70,61,46,46,33,17,0,30,8,21,2,25,11,16,16,30,
16,57,53,56,31,26,27,27,16]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4
Nc6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O a5 10. Bb5 (10. a4 Nb4 11. f4 Be6 {
[%cal Rd6d5]} 12. f5 Bxb3 (12... Bd7 {[%cal Rd7c6]} 13. Bf3 (13. Kh1 Qc7 {
[%cal Rf8d8,Rd8d5]}) 13... d5 14. exd5 Bxf5) 13. cxb3 d5) 10... Be6 11. f3 Na7
12. Bd3 Nc8 13. Qe2 Nb6 14. Qf2 Nc4 15. Bxc4 Bxc4 16. Rfd1 Qb8 {[%cal Yb7b5]} (
16... a4 {looked tempting as well but I was concerned the knight would
transfer to d5 via c1, d3 and b4}) 17. Na4 (17. a4 Be6 {[%cal Rf8c8]}) 17... b5
(17... Nd7 $5 18. Nd2 Be6 19. c4 b5 20. cxb5 Qxb5 21. b3 {[%cal Ra4c3,Rc3d5]}
f5 22. Nc3 Qb7 23. Qe1 $15 {[%csl Rd6,Re5,Re7]}) 18. Nb6 Ra6 19. a4 (19. Nxc4
bxc4 {[%cal Rb8b2]} 20. Nd2 Rc6 {[%cal Yb8b2]} 21. Rab1 Qc7 (21... d5 22. exd5
Nxd5 23. Nxc4 Nxe3 24. Nxe3 Bc5 25. Kh1 Bxe3 26. Qxe3 Rxc2) 22. c3 Rd8 {
[%cal Rd6d5]}) 19... Bd8 {forcing White to capture and change the structure}
20. Nxc4 bxc4 21. Nd2 Rc6 {I wanted to keep the c4 pawn on board: taking Qxb2
would simplify the position too much} 22. b3 cxb3 23. Nxb3 (23. cxb3 d5 $15 {
[%csl Re3][%cal Yc6g6,Yf6d5,Yd5f4,Yd5e3] Black will soon dominate the dark
squares}) 23... Qc7 {preparing Rc4 and looking to exploit the numerous white
weaknesses} 24. Ra2 Be7 {[%cal Rf8c8,Rc8a8]} 25. Qe2 Ra8 {overprotecting the
only weak spot in Black's position} 26. g4 $2 {can only be described as
desperation} h6 27. h4 Nh7 28. Qf2 Qd8 {fixating White's structure} 29. h5 Ng5
{[%cal Rg5h3,Rg5e6]} 30. Bxg5 Bxg5 $19 {The White knight has no realistic
prospects of ever making it back into the game while the Black bishop controls
all the important dark squares} 31. Rd5 Qc7 32. Qe2 Rc3 33. Rd3 Rb8 34. Kg2 Rb4
35. Rxc3 Qxc3 36. Nxa5 Rb1 {[%csl Rg2] Black's attack is unstoppable as the
stranded White rook and the knight cannot help the king} 37. Nb3 Be3 38. a5 Re1
{[%cal Re1g1,Re1e2]} 0-1

