{[%evp 0,122,19,14,40,46,50,29,14,14,12,39,42,18,19,19,23,25,23,0,0,-12,-4,-8,
21,9,7,21,21,21,-3,-24,-5,-18,11,0,13,13,22,16,8,15,29,-6,-20,-1,-1,-15,-10,
-15,-15,-40,-26,-30,-7,-25,-32,-21,-21,-12,-2,1,0,0,-10,-9,0,-25,7,-57,0,-55,
-54,-74,-85,-100,-36,-52,-83,-311,-100,-210,-126,-114,-108,-108,-111,-111,-111,
-119,-114,-150,-117,-103,-116,-143,-165,-196,-203,-211,-203,-240,-261,-255,
-298,-279,-308,-245,-245,-244,-267,-271,-267,-263,-266,-276,-274,-284,-260,
-284,-260,-271,-268,-268,-275]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {People often forget that
as a rising star Kramnik used to go for the Classical Sicilian before
switching to the rock solid lines he is famous for: the Berlin and the Petroff}
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nf3 h6 (7... Be7 8. Bg5) 8. h3
Be6 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 Rc8 {[%cal Yc8c3] a move order preventing setups with b3
} (10... O-O 11. Bf1 Nb8 (11... Qa5 $6 {[%cal Rc3d5]} 12. Bd2 {[%cal Rc3d5]}
Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rd1d6]} 13. Nb5 Qb8 14. c4)) 11. Bf1 Nb8 {[%csl Rc3][%cal
Rc8c3,Rb2b3]} (11... O-O 12. Nd5 Bxd5 (12... Nxd5 13. exd5) 13. exd5 Nb8 14. c4
Nbd7 15. Nh4 $16 {[%cal Rh4f5]}) 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Bf5 14. c4 (14. Bd3 Qd7
15. c4 O-O 16. Bxf5 Qxf5 17. b3 Qg6 18. Ba3 {[%cal Rf3e5]} Rfe8 19. Nd2 f5 $15
{[%cal Rb8d7]}) 14... O-O 15. Qa4 {against every other move, Black would play
Nd7} a5 $15 16. a3 {A critical moment for the game: White is ready to push b4
so Black needs to react accordingly} Bd7 (16... Nd7 {surprisingly this move
works out perfectly due to} 17. b4 Ra8 $1 $17 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ra5b4] A
fantastic quiet move! Black threatens axb4 next move and there is no way to
counter it without concessions. White has to either push b5 (surrendering c5),
or take on b4 with the queen and lose the flexibility of his structure} 18. b5
(18. Qb5 axb4 19. Qxb4 (19. Qxb7 Rb8 20. Qa6 Nc5) 19... Nc5 20. Be3 b6 {
[%csl Rb6][%cal Rf5b1]}) 18... Nc5 19. Qd1 a4 $19 {[%csl Rb5,Rc4,Rd5][%cal
Rf5h7,Rf7f5,Re5e4]}) 17. Qd1 a4 {making sure White does not connect his pawns}
18. b4 axb3 19. Qxb3 Na6 {[%cal Ya6c5] sacrificing b7 so that Black's
counterplay in the center is a typical idea in the position} 20. Be3 (20. Qxb7
$6 Nc5 $17 21. Qb1 f5 22. Be3 e4 {Black has marvelous compensation for the
pawn. White's extra pawn does not make any difference as he is getting
steamrolled in the center} 23. Nd4 f4 24. Bd2 Rb8 $17 (24... e3 {is a standard
resource used to open up lines} 25. fxe3 Bh4 $15) 25. Bb4 e3 26. fxe3 Bh4 {
[%cal Rh4f2,Rf4e3]}) 20... Qc7 21. a4 Nc5 22. Bxc5 Qxc5 23. Qxb7 Rc7 24. Qb3
Ra8 $44 {Black has the bishop pair, total control over the dark squares and a
pawn majority in the center to make up for the sacrificed material} 25. Nd2 f5
26. Nb1 Bh4 {provoking 27.g3 so that f4 comes with a greater force later} 27.
g3 Bf6 28. Nc3 e4 29. Ra2 Qa5 30. Rc1 Be5 {centralizing the bishop} 31. Rcc2
Rc5 32. Nb5 Kh8 {a prophylactic move avoiding any possible checks in the future
} 33. Qe3 Qb4 34. Nd4 Rcc8 35. Ne6 Rxa4 {regaining the material} (35... Bxa4)
36. Rxa4 Qxa4 37. Rd2 $6 Qa1 38. Kg2 Rb8 $15 {[%cal Yb8b1,Yb1e1,Ye1f1]} 39. Nf4
$2 Rb1 $19 {the rest is just a matter of technique} 40. Qe2 Re1 41. Ra2 Rxe2
42. Rxa1 Rxf2+ 43. Kxf2 Bxa1 44. Ke3 Kg8 45. Ne6 g6 46. c5 Be5 47. g4 Bxe6 48.
dxe6 d5 49. gxf5 gxf5 50. Bb5 Kf8 51. Bc6 d4+ 52. Kd2 Bf4+ 53. Kc2 d3+ 54. Kc3
Be3 55. Kc4 Ke7 56. Kd5 Bxc5 57. Bb5 Bd6 58. Bc4 Bc7 59. Bb5 Kf6 60. h4 Bg3 61.
h5 Bc7 0-1

