{[%evp 0,61,19,38,40,41,51,18,45,29,49,34,35,44,50,48,46,29,29,19,46,20,15,21,
27,21,21,21,13,15,11,-43,-50,-34,-50,-50,-49,-49,-17,-55,-2,-32,-51,-16,-14,
-71,-33,-91,-14,-18,-42,-62,12,-47,-40,-46,27,27,72,72,330,447,527,831]} 1. e4
c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 {The Rauzer is
considered to be the main and the most dangerous weapon for White against
Classical Sicilian.} e6 7. Qd2 {With Black's knight on c6, White can't play
the setup with f4 and Qf3. He needs to choose between 7.Qd2 and 7.Qd3} Be7 8.
O-O-O O-O 9. Nb3 {White is avoiding the exchange Nxd4.} (9. f3 {right now this
move is not very accurate because it allows d5} d5 $11) 9... Qb6 {This is a
prophylactic against Bxf6 followed by Qxd6} 10. f3 {White has two setups: an
immediate f4 or f3-g4} a6 11. g4 Rd8 12. Be3 {White freeing the g5 square with
tempo} Qc7 {The drawback of 9...Qb6 is that it blocks the b-pawn} 13. g5 Nd7 (
13... Nh5 {Sometimes Black prefers this square for the knight, but in this
case, White can attack the knight quickly via f4 and Be2.}) 14. h4 b5 15. g6 $1
{A well-known attacking method which you need to remember. White is not
wasting time for h5 and immediately starts the attack} fxg6 (15... hxg6 16. h5
{is even worse for Black}) 16. h5 gxh5 17. Rxh5 Nf6 18. Rg5 Ne5 19. Qg2 Bf8 20.
Be2 {[%cal Rf3f4,Rd1h1]} Nc4 21. Bxc4 bxc4 22. Nd4 Rb8 23. Rh1 {[%cal Rc3d1]}
Rb7 24. Rh6 Kf7 25. Rh4 Qb6 26. Nd1 Qc7 27. f4 h6 28. Rg6 Re8 29. f5 e5 30. Nc3
Qd8 31. Nc6 {An elegant finish of the game. The g5-g6 push without h5 becomes
a trademark of Mihail Tal and he won many games with this idea.} 1-0

