{[%evp 0,48,19,19,41,56,46,12,19,8,32,47,63,47,63,27,51,63,40,33,33,33,38,77,
74,-6,-12,26,-1,6,6,-209,-271,-225,16,-155,17,-214,-252,-272,-315,-374,-300,
-311,-177,-1885,-1904,-1904,-1933,-29997,-29998]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 Bd7 {This is a tricky system. Many times in
Rauzer, Black develops first the queenside and then the kingside} 7. Qd2 Rc8 {
Black is trying to organize a quick counterplay on the c-file. The variation
is considered better for White, but it is quite tricky} 8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4
Qa5 {As you see, Black ignores the kingside completely. Now the threats are
Rxc3 (typical idea in all Sicilians) and Qxg5} 10. f4 (10. Bxf6 {Is the other
way for White to continue, but looks quite harmless} gxf6) 10... Rxc3 11. bxc3
(11. Qxc3 {White can enter an endgame, but as a rule, Black is doing fine in
such positions. He has a pawn for the exchange and a better structure.} Qxc3
12. bxc3 Nxe4) 11... e5 $1 {an important motif. The attack can't be successful
without the help of the other pieces, especially the dark-squared bishop.} 12.
Qc4 $2 (12. Qb4 $5 {is the best move for White with a very complicated
position.}) 12... d5 $1 {The advance d6-d5 is an essential idea after e7-e5}
13. exd5 Ba3+ 14. Kd2 Nxd5 15. Re1 f6 16. Rb1 O-O 17. Rxb7 Rc8 18. Rxa7 $2 {
After this mistake, the game is practically over} (18. Rb5 $5 Qxc3+ 19. Qxc3
Nxc3 20. Rb3 fxg5 21. Ba6) 18... Qxa7 19. Qxd5+ Kh8 20. Bh4 Bc6 21. Qe6 Bc1+
22. Ke1 Qe3+ 23. Be2 Rd8 24. Bf2 Rd1+ 0-1

