1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4 {Probably the
sharpest system for White.} e6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Qe2 {This time the queen is not
forced to stay on d-file.} O-O 9. O-O-O a6 10. Bb3 Qe8 {Black is defending
against any e4-e5 threats} 11. Rhg1 {White is trying to play without f4} (11.
g4 $2 Nxd4 $1 {remember this typical idea for Black} 12. Bxd4 e5 13. Be3 Bxg4)
11... Nd7 12. g4 {That's the right time for starting the attack.} Nc5 13. g5 b5
14. Nxc6 Nxb3+ 15. axb3 Qxc6 16. Qh5 {This time, White has another way to
start an attack. This is another important attacking approach. The combination
Rg1-Qh5-Bd4 is very dangerous. Now the threat is Qh6 in many lines} b4 17. Bd4
$1 {Brilliant move.} Bb7 (17... bxc3 $2 18. Qh6 $3 $18) 18. Nd5 $1 {This is
always the first move which you should consider} exd5 19. Rd3 $3 {Another very
nice attacking move} (19. Qh6 {is not working now because of} Qxc2+ $1 20. Kxc2
Rfc8+ $1 21. Kb1 gxh6 22. gxh6+ Kf8 $19 {and Black wins}) 19... Rfc8 20. c3 {
simple and strong. Now Black's attack is over and White's threads are
unstoppable.} bxc3 21. bxc3 dxe4 22. Rh3 Kf8 23. g6 $1 {The last important
resource. It wasn't too late to lose the game after:} (23. Qxh7 $2 Ke8 $1 24.
g6 Qd5 {and Black wins}) 23... fxg6 24. Qxh7 Ke8 25. Rxg6 Qb5 26. Rxg7 Bg5+ 27.
Re3 Bxe3+ 28. fxe3 Qf1+ 29. Kb2 1-0

