1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 Be7 {This is the current fashion in Rauzer.} 10. Nf3 {White is
avoiding the exchange Nxd4} b5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 {In this structure, Black's king
can't go to the kingside anymore. So he should prepare a long castle now.} 12.
Kb1 Qb6 13. f5 O-O-O 14. g3 Kb8 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Bh3 Na5 $1 {Black starts his
own counterplay against White's king. The threat is b4 followed by e5. With
the knight on "a5", White can't answer b4 with Na4, because the d7-bishop is
covering the square.} (16... Bc8) 17. Nd4 ({for example} 17. Rhe1 {is well met
with} b4 18. Ne2 e5 $1 {White has two knights but neither of them can go to
"d5 very easy}) 17... b4 18. Nce2 e5 {White finally succeeds with his plan to
provoke the advance e6-e5.} 19. Bxd7 Rxd7 20. Nf5 Nc4 21. Qd3 Rc8 22. Nc1 a5
23. Nb3 d5 $1 {Remember, guys, after the advance e5, Black always should
consider d6-d5.} 24. exd5 a4 25. Nd2 $2 ({My engine insist on this but I
believe Black's compensation is more than enough after:} 25. Nxe7 Rxe7 $44)
25... Na3+ $1 26. bxa3 Rc3 $1 27. Qe2 $2 ({This was White's last chance to
stay in the game.} 27. Nc4 Qc5 28. d6 Rxd3 29. cxd3 $17) 27... bxa3+ 28. Nb3
axb3 29. cxb3 Rxb3+ $1 {Now Black's attack is unstoppable.} 30. Ka1 Rb2 31. Rb1
Bb4 32. Qe3 Qb5 33. Rhd1 (33. Rxb2 axb2+ 34. Kb1 Qxd5 $19) 33... Qc4 34. Rxb2
axb2+ 35. Kb1 Rc7 36. Qb6+ Ka8 0-1

