1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O h6 {Another approach is to play with an early h6.} 9. Nxc6 $1 (9. Bh4 $6
Nxe4 $1 $15 {is a typical}) 9... bxc6 10. Bf4 d5 11. Qe3 Bb4 12. Be2 Qa5 (12...
O-O 13. e5 {is the main theory and is discussed in the next games.}) 13. Be5
Bb7 14. Kb1 O-O-O {Evacuating the king on the queenside is just wrong in this
structure.} 15. exd5 cxd5 16. a3 Bf8 {another move that is hard to understand.}
17. Rd3 $1 {Very good move. White is doubling the rooks, transferring the rook
to 3rd rank and preparing b2-b4.} Nd7 18. b4 (18. Nxd5 $3 {ends the game
immediately.}) 18... Qb6 (18... Qxa3 19. Nxd5) 19. Bd4 Qd6 20. f4 $1 {White
should not allow e5} Bc6 21. Ka1 f6 22. Bg4 $1 {another prophylactic move
against e5.} Re8 23. Re1 g5 24. g3 Bg7 25. Bxe6 $16 {White wins material now.}
Kb7 26. f5 Ne5 27. Bc5 Qb8 28. Bxd5 {White has different ways to convert his
big advantage, but the way which the Dutch IM chose was very effective as well}
Nxd3 29. Bxc6+ Kxc6 30. Qf3+ Kc7 31. Rxe8 {Now the game is over.} Qxe8 32. Qxd3
Qe5 33. Ka2 Rd8 34. Qxa6 Rb8 35. Qa7+ Kc8 36. Qxg7 Qxc3 37. Qf8+ Kb7 38. Qe7+
Kc8 39. Qe6+ Kc7 40. Qd6+ 1-0

