{[#] In this position White wants to play b4. How Black can deal with this?} 
13... Nb8 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} 14. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5]} (14. b4 $6 Qc7 $146 15. Bb2
a6 $15 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6] White's c4-square is weak and Black is
plans to play ...Nbd7-b6.}) (14. Be3 Nbd7 15. Nd2 a6 16. Be2 b5 17. Bf3 Qc7 18.
Nf1 Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c4]} 19. Bxb6 Qxb6 $15 {[%cal Ga8b8,Ga6a5,Gb6c5] 1/2 (36)
Pauli,A (2388)-Gil,M (2296) GER email 2007}) (14. Bd2 Qc7 15. Bd3 Nbd7 16. Qe2
Nc5 17. Bc4 a6 18. Bxe6 fxe6 $1 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ge6f5] This the correct recapture.
Black's e6-pawn controls the important squares f5 and d5.} 19. a4 Ncd7 20. Qd3
Qc6 21. Rbc1 Nc5 22. Qc4 b5 $1 23. axb5 axb5 24. Qb4 (24. Qxb5 Qxb5 25. Nxb5
Rab8 $17 {Black has a clear advantage.}) (24. Nxb5 Rcb8 $15 {Black is slighlty
better.}) 24... Qb7 25. Rcd1 {1-0 (43) Vertongen,W (2377)-Fajs,B (2490) ICCF
email 2008} Kf7 $17) 14... Nc6 {White does not have a better option than
repeating moves.} ({If Black does not want to make a draw} 14... Rd8 $5 $146 {
is also an interesting alternative and after} 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. exf5 Nc6 $13 {
The position is unclear.}) 15. Nf3 (15. Nf5 $6 $146 Bxf5 16. exf5 d5 $15 {
Black's central pawns are very strong.}) 15... Nb8 $11 {Draw by move
repetition.} *

